<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, Swedish FMs Disappointed at U.S. Senate's Rejection of CTBT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from
Germany and Sweden, Joschka Fischer and Anna Lindh, said here
today that they were deeply disappointed at a U.S. Senate decision
to reject the ratification of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (
CTBT), a global pact targeted at ending nuclear tests worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate decision represents a serious setback for
nuclear non-proliferation and disarmament and is therefore a wrong
signal, said the foreign ministers in a joint statement, adding
that they "deeply regret" the rejection.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers expressed the hope that President Clinton and
his administration would find a way to make the United States a
full supporter of the CTBT, and called on other nations across the
world to continue with their efforts of disarmament and nuclear
non-proliferation, which include the signing and ratification of
the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Fischer arrived in Stockholm on Wednesday for a two-day visit
at the invitation of the Swedish government. He is to hold talks
with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov later on Thursday. The
two will reportedly focus on the situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said at a press conference here that Germany believes
the conflict in Chechnya can be settled only through dialogue, and
the European Union and the United States is concerned about the
current fighting in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
However, sources within the German Foreign Ministry earlier
ruled out any possibility that Fischer would, on behalf of the
western nations, present a special proposal on the resolution of
the Chechnya issue to the Russian side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
