<HEADLINE> Thailand's Bank of Asia Rated Investment Grade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) - Fitch IBCA assigned Thursday
investment grade foreign currency ratings to Bank of Asia (BOA) at
'BBB-' Long-term and 'F3' Short-term.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the international rating agency also affirmed
BOA's Individual and Support ratings at 'D/E' and '3',
respectively.
</P>
<P>
These debt ratings are the highest the agency has assigned to a
Thai Bank. The ratings factor in the strong likelihood of
shareholder support from Bank of Asia's parent, ABN AMRO Bank NV,
which currently owns 75 percent of issued shares, according to
Fitch IBCA.
</P>
<P>
BOA was established in 1939 and currently ranks as the 10th
largest commercial bank in Thailand, with a share of deposits and
loans of approximately 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fitch IBCA expects a significant improvement in Bank of Asia's
management of credit risks, business development, profitability
and operating standards that should transform it into one of
Thairland's premier banking units during the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
