<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three-Fourths of Pakistanis Support Army Action: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Approximately three out of
four Pakistanis supported the army action to dismiss the
government led by Nawaz Sharif, shows a snap poll conducted by
Gallup Pakistan in various cities of the country on the evening of
October 13.
</P>
<P>
The poll findings should, however, be read with the caution
that opinions on such issues can be quite volatile and may change
fairly rapidly in response to the unfolding situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll results released Thursday, some 75
percent of those sampled approved the action taken by the army.
But only one-third favored direct military rule and the remaining
two-thirds supported a civilian government.
</P>
<P>
From within civilian choices, 75 percent favored a government
comprising non-political reputable experts; support for returning
government to Pakistan Muslim League (PML) leaders including
Sharif is less than 10 percent, and support for forming a national
government of respectable politicians of political parties is
around 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the initial response within hours of the military action,
when asked would they favor an election in less than 90 days or
after two or three days, around 60 percent chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
Concerning expectations from the post-Sharif setup a majority
were not very hopeful of a turnaround in the economic situation;
only 25 percent were hopeful of a respite in inflation or
unemployment. But around 80 percent were hopeful that the law and
order situation will improve.
</P>
<P>
The survey findings nevertheless reveal that despite the
widespread approval of Sharif's removal from office, PML is still
the largest single vote bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
Those who said they would still vote for PML in a future
election outnumber any other political party in the country.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted with a randomly drawn sample of over
850 men and women in the urban areas of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
