<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Experts Report Serious Pollution in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.N.
environment experts Thursday said that they have detected serious
pollution and called for "immediate clean-up action" in Serbia, a
Yugoslav republic which was hardest-hit by 78-day NATO air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was contained in a report issued here Thursday by
the Balkan Task Force (BTF) jointly organized by the United
Nations Environment Program and the U.N. Center for Human
Settlements (UNCHS/Habitat), which conducted a fact-finding work
in four environmental "hot spots" in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"Pollution detected at four environmental 'hot spots' is
serious and poses a threat to human health," a UNEP press release
said. The four sites are in Pancevo, Kragujevac, Novi Sad and Bor
in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"At these sites, all in Serbia, immediate clean-up action,
which should be seen as a part of humanitarian assistance to the
region, is called for," the news release said.
</P>
<P>
The BTF report, entitled "The Kosovo Conflict -- Consequences
for the Environment and Human Settlements," also concludes that in
Kosovo the human settlement problem is not just about
reconstructing houses, but a question of establishing
administrative procedures that will give people security of
tenure.
</P>
<P>
"In a post-conflict situation, such a neutral, objective and
scientific assessment of the real situation on the ground is
essential," said Klaus Toepfer, executive director of the UNEP and
UNCHS.
</P>
<P>
"As part of the humanitarian aid to the region, the
international community should assist the relevant authorities in
dealing with the key environmental hot spots, thus avoiding
further harm to human health and the environment in Yugoslavia and
the wider Balkans region," said Pekka Haavisto, the former Finnish
Environment and Development Cooperation Minister, who is on the
BTF.
</P>
<P>
Without the authorisation of the U.N. Security Council, NATO
began air strikes on March 24 on Yugoslavia, a sovereign member of
the U.N. family, seriously violating the U.N. Charter and
international law, and also causing serious environmental problems
in the Balkans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0019 </DOCNO>
