<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland "Happy Enough" To Play Turks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Republic of Ireland soccer team
manager Mick McCarthy put a brave face on his team's tough Euro
2000 play-off draw against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
It means the Irish will have their hopes of reaching the finals
next summer decided among the boiling hostility of Istanbul when
the second leg is played on Wednesday, November 17.
</P>
<P>
But McCarthy said: "It is the team we will be playing against,
not anything else. I'm happy enough with the draw because we
avoided the ones I wanted to avoid - England, because of all the
hype that would have entailed; and Ukraine, because they are by
far the best team in the play-offs with two great strikers in
Andriy Shevchenko and Sergi Rebrov."
</P>
<P>
Turkey beat Euro 96 champions Germany 1-0 in Group Three a year
ago and were assured of runners-up place before earning only a
goalless draw in the return in Munich on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
They also twice beat Northern Ireland 3-0. But McCarthy, who
will seek pointers on the Turks from Northern Ireland boss Lawrie
McMenemy, said: "The biggest disappointment is that we are playing
the away leg second, but Turkey won't fancy coming to Dublin
either.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever way you look at it you know it is going to be down to
who performs best on the day. It may be a difficult trip for our
fans to Istanbul - but even if we have to go there with just the
squad of 22 we'll give it a real go."
</P>
<P>
Ireland's last meeting with Turkey was on November 13, 1991 in
the final European Championship qualifier in Istanbul when Jack
Charlton's team - with McCarthy at center-back - won 3-1 thanks to
two goals by John Byrne of Sunderland and another by Tony
Cascarino who, now 37, is just one goal short of the all-time
Republic record of 20.
</P>
<P>
It was a magnificent performance by Ireland but not enough to
earn them a place in the finals in Sweden because England's draw
in Poland on the same night won the group. There were no play-offs
for second-placed teams then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0029 </DOCNO>
