<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England Hold No Fears for Brown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Scotland manager Craig Brown is
savoring the prospect of a two-legged play-off against England to
secure a place at Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
Brown's team were the first name out of the hat and will face
the Auld Enemy for the first time since the 2-0 Euro 96 defeat at
Wembley, with Alan Shearer and Paul Gascoigne scoring for England
and Gary McAllister missing a crucial penalty.
</P>
<P>
But Brown said: "I am not surprised by the draw and I'm quite
relaxed about it. I think the England team were stronger in Euro
96 and I don't think we need fear them."
</P>
<P>
He added: "The unfortunate thing for England is that one of us
has to go through. Of course we are not under-estimating them;
England are very strong in attack and have great experience at the
back.
</P>
<P>
"We are just hoping we get everybody fit for the two games, and
they should be a couple of great matches."
</P>
<P>
The first match against England is due to be played at Hampden
Park on November 13, with the return leg at Wembley the following
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brown said: "We are lucky the new stadium is now complete, and
there will be a full house. It should be a wonderful atmosphere
and a wonderful occasion."
</P>
<P>
He intends to take in a number of Premiership games in England
in the next month, along with his number two Alex Miller who is
now scouting for Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
"I know most of the England players - but one or two I'm unsure
about, like Frank Lampard. It would be good to see them at first
hand." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Boxer Dies After Knockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan boxer Carlos Barreto
died on Tuesday from head injuries sustained from a knockout in a
fight last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old, former interim World Boxing Association super
bantamweight champion, had a fight on Saturday against compatriot
Jose Luis Valbuena for the Latin American super bantamweight title.
Barreto was knocked out in the 10th round.
</P>
<P>
Barreto fell unconscious after a blow from Valbuena and died
Tuesday during a coma.
</P>
<P>
He kept the interim WBA champion title in his weight category
from October to November 1998, temporarily holding the title while
Mexico's Enrique Sanchez recovered from an injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Zberg Wins Italian Cycle Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's Marcus Zberg, silver
medalist in the elite road race in the recent world championships,
outsprinted Paolo Bettini and world time trial champion Jan
Ullrich on Wednesday to win the Milan-to-Turin cycling classic.
</P>
<P>
Zberg covered the 202-kilometer race in a time of four hours,
24 minutes and 55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Spainard Oscar Freire Gomez, who beat Zberg for the road race
title at the world championships in Verona last Sunday, finished 1:
38 minutes behind the winner, in 38th place.
</P>
<P>
Other top finishers included Sweden's Niklas Axelsson, fourth,
and American Chann McRae, sixth, all in the same time as the
winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
