<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Improve Drainage System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
decided to overhaul sewage and drainage systems in capital
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Committee on national economy has endorsed
the city council's request for a 5.4-million-U.S. dollar loan from
the World Bank, Radio Uganda reported Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The legislature will try to ask the world financial institution
to release the loan before November 17 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor John Ssebaana Kizito, the money will be used
to build Nakivubo Channel Project and improve the drainage systems
which have been neglected for many years.
</P>
<P>
Kampala's roads are characterized by deep potholes and poor
quality. The drainage system is so poor that there is almost
always flooding after a downpour. The flooding causes halt of
business, traffic jams and power breakdown.
</P>
<P>
There have been loud outcries for the improvement of the
infrastructures such as road and drainage in Kampala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
