<HEADLINE> Prosecutor Orders DNA Tests On Pantani Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- An Italian prosecutor ordered DNA
tests on the blood of Marco Pantani, the Italian cycling star
Marco Pantani, who was banned from the Giro d"Italia or Tour of
Italy in June after failing a blood test.
</P>
<P>
The random tests showed his count of red cells exceeded the
legal level of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Bruno Giardina's office said in Trento, Italy on
Wednesday that the tests were intended to prove if the blood
samples actually belonged to Pantani and if tests that led to
Pantani's ban from the race were properly handled by the ICU
medical staff.
</P>
<P>
Tests might also reveal if the samples taken from Pantani and
10 other cyclists on the eve of the race's next-to-last stage
contained natural or artificial substances.
</P>
<P>
Pantani, a double Giro and Tour of France winner in 1998, was
suspended for two weeks and prevented from completing the Giro
which he was dominating.
</P>
<P>
A high count of red blood cells might signal the use of the
banned growth hormone EPO, but can also occur naturally.
</P>
<P>
Pantani has not been competing since his suspension in the Giro
but said recently he planned to return from a knee injury to
action next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
