<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Makes High Debut at Gymnastics World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is looking forward to a
historic bronze medal after they vaulted to a flying start in the
women's horse vault qualifying competition of the world gymnastics
championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Denisse Lopez entered the finals after finishing third
in the qualifiers and became the first world championships
finalist in the nation's 72-year history in the sport.
</P>
<P>
The surprising delight came when the country fielded both men's
and women's teams for world championships for the first time in
the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
It was a great encouragement to Sanchez, president of the
Mexico Gymnastics Federation who took the post two months ago.
</P>
<P>
"I were just elected two months ago, and I think it is really
hard to come here, so we make analysis of the situation and got
the best gymnasts of the country," said Sanchez. "We also got
support from the sponsors, so we have the responsibility to work
hard."
</P>
<P>
"Before the games we had a target of one qualifier for the 2000
Sydney Olympics, now we did that," said Sanchez. "It means a lot
for us. The government is going to put more attention into our
program."
</P>
<P>
"It was really a good news for the Mexicans, for the team are
still young and inexperienced," Sanchez said of his country whose
gymnastics program started from scratch 72 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"If she can win a medal, even a bronze medal, Mexico will have
a fiesta, a bigger party," Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
But Rome is not built overnight as the country has geared up
for international glory although it remains a big challenge for
them to get further.
</P>
<P>
"In the past there were no gymnastics programs in public
schools but in the past three years the government have started to
put in the programs. For us gymnastics is everything, it is the
basics of the sports."
</P>
<P>
They also have foreign coaches to get the gymnastics wilderness
updated with the development of the sport and produced good local
coaches which have been a far cry for them.
</P>
<P>
"Russian coaches came to give us advice and classes, Cuban
coaches stayed for one year through the interchange program, and
we have 35 Bulgarian coaches all over the country," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
After seeing China ended up with the men's team gold and women'
s team bronze, Sanchez has turned his eyes on the Chinese coaches.
</P>
<P>
"I will start talking with the Chinese coaches, and tomorrow I
will go to the Mexican Embassy in Beijing and talk with the
ambassador about this. I know between China and Mexico we have
interchange program," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez was also aware of the problem that gymnastics is still
an amateur sport in his country.
</P>
<P>
"We maybe not good at basketball or wrestling, but our
constitution is good enough to play soccer, cycling and gymnastics.
And they are also talented.
</P>
<P>
"But they need time to work. It is hard for most of them are
University students. They can only spend five or six hours a day.
</P>
<P>
"Our federation has talked with the parents and principles of
universities and tried to persuade them to allow time for the
gymnasts. So in a sense parents and head of the universities are
also part of the team for the championships. We cannot do without
their support," said Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
But the ambitious president expressed his full confidence to
have a strong team in the future.
</P>
<P>
"I think in the next Olympic cycle we will be more motivated,
more experienced with more international competition."
</P>
<P>
A philosophy is the thing that stands behind him.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing impossible in this world and the only thing
that have no solution is death," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
