<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grandi: Degree of Difficulty Can't Grow without Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Acrobatics or Artistry? Which
choice should gymnastics take for its future?
</P>
<P>
"We prefer the balance between them and will control the degree
of difficulty with new scoring rules," said Bruno Grandi,
president of the International Gymnastics Federation, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We will take into account both the factor of execution and
degree of difficulty when we are developing the new rules for
judging," said the president who has brought gymnastics under
reform since he came into power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There have been mixed reactions to the to-be-finalized new Code
of Points which de facto has encouraged the gymnasts to pursue
more difficult routines.
</P>
<P>
"Gymnastics has made some progress in terms of difficulty
degree, but the unbridled development in degree of difficulty can
not go too far,"said Grandi.
</P>
<P>
The president advised gymnasts not to rely on tricks to win
because they will be likely to miss both artistry and technique at
one time.
</P>
<P>
"Not everyone can perform difficult tricks and sometimes the
poorly performed routines will backfire and destroy the cleanness
and elegance."
</P>
<P>
He said that the FIG will control the development of the very
difficult tricks for it is "dangerous and will tarnish the image
of the gymnastics".
</P>
<P>
But this is not the only reason why he aims to put the degree
of difficulty under rein.
</P>
<P>
"The tricks may surprise you but it will not last long. While
the artistry can impress the spectators for quite a long time. So
to keep the vitality and vigor of gymnastics we need to be
artistic," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Like the landing on the moon it might create a sensation but
just lasts for some time. It is the same case with gymnastics
whose tricks may become commonplace as more and more gymnasts can
perform it."
</P>
<P>
"What makes gymnastics distinct from the other sports is their
artistic and cultural aspects." the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the FIG will work out rules and
regulations for scoring and all gymnasts are expected to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
"Now the problem is that the scoring rules have been led by the
abnormal development in the degree of difficulty. We should let
them meet the requirements of the rules and not the other way
around."
</P>
<P>
When asked if Svetlana Khorkina of Russia, who is famous more
for artistry than tricks, will be one of the models for the future
direction of gymnastics, the president said:"Why not?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
