<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Maria Olaru Claims Women's All-Around Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A new generation of gymnasts
stole the limelight by impeccable performance as Maria Olaru of
Romania rallied to win the women's all-around title at the
gymnastics World Championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Olaru, the hottest contender for the title,
surged to claim the victory with an aggregate score of 38.774
points, followed by Vyctoria Karpenko of Ukraine in 38.705 and
Elena Zamolodchikova of Russia 38.687, respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Today's competition is in a way that looks like the team final
on Tuesday because it is until the last apparatus that the final
result is clear, " said the Romanian head coach Octavian Bellu.
</P>
<P>
Olaru, 1.61cm, silver medalist at Goodwill Games in the United
States last year, planted her name into everyone's heart when she
led through the qualifying ground and team final with flawless
routines, of which were all above 9.600 points.
</P>
<P>
However, she placed seventh after her first rotation on the
uneven bars in today's finals, fourth after the beam in 9.737, and
second overall before she scored a decisive 9.625 in the last
apparatus of the vault. The score was good enough for her to edge
pace-setter Karpenko by 0.69 points for the title.
</P>
<P>
Karpenko led after the third rotation, suffered a weak vault of
9.493 points and had to settle for the silver medal.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Elena Produnova of Russia won the fourth in 38.
675, ahead of Andreea Raducan of Romania 38.617. Chinese Dong
Fangxiao and Huang Mandan ranked fifth and sixth in 38.143 and 38.
018, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Svetlana Khorkina of Russia finished a
distant 12th for 37.611 points, while her long-time rival Simona
Amanar of Romania, Atlanta Olympics vault champion and all-around
runner-up in 1997, ranked 14th overall with 37.299.
</P>
<P>
Amanar, third overall before her lethal falling down from the
uneven bars, her last apparatus, slipt away the chance of winning
the title.
</P>
<P>
"Time has changed and the young are pushing the experienced who
are tired to resist the pressure, like Simona Amanar and Khorkina.
But the young are hungry for the medals and success," Bellu said.
</P>
<P>
"We deeply respect Simona and Khorkina, They will be in the
2000 Olympics, it is a great credit to them, " added Bellu.
</P>
<P>
Russian coach Marina Boulachenko agreed with legend Romanian
coach Bellu and said: "One defeat does not tell everything of
stars like Khorkina and Amanar. And I'm sure them are to come back
at the Sydney Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gymnasts: Like Father Like Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Gymnastics is believed to be a
sport of talents and  usually a family heredity leads young
gymnasts to the way of success.
</P>
<P>
That's true in the current Tianjin world championships when
gymnastics family got together with fathers and son and daughters
competing and coaching under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
Japan's leading gymnast Naoya Tsukahara is the son of Tsukahara,
the 1972 Olympic and 1970 world champion and inventor of the
Tsukahara Vault and Tsukahara Dismount of High Bar. The junior
Tsukahara tried every effort to emulate his famous father and led
the Japanese men's team to a fourth place in the final.
</P>
<P>
Naoya's teammate Akihiro Kasamatsu also came from a famous
gymnastics family. Akihiro's father, Shigeru Kasamatsu, will never
be forgotten because of the tragedy in 1976 Montreal Olympic Games,
where the senior Kasamatsu had to undergo an appendix operation
just days prior to what should have been his Olympic gold medal
competition.
</P>
<P>
But Akihiro and Naoya, the "brothers in arms", will try to
retrieve their family glory and spearhead the Japanese team to the
medal podium in next year's Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Besides the father-son gymnasts, great coaches also have a role
to play to guide their children to be the world class gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Carballo, a former national coach for the Spanish men's
and women's team, is the father of the 1996 world champion on high
bar Jesus Carballo-Junior.
</P>
<P>
Jana Komrskova of Czech Republic surged into the all-around
competition as a surprise. Jana is named after her father, Jan
Komrskov, who is the Czech national coach and was used to
dominating the world with star gymnast Vera Caslavska.
</P>
<P>
Yewki Yomita, 19, the youngest gymnast in the United States
team in Tianjin, who competed in the Individual all-around final
on Thursday, is also coached by his father Yoichi Yomita, who
competed for the American national team in 1979-80.
</P>
<P>
Krisztian Jordanov is one of the best gymnasts in the Hungarian
team. He was so sad about his team's failure to qualify for the
Sydney Olympic Games by finishing 13th in the team final. The
coach who comforted him was his father, Zoltan Jordanov, whose
father and Krisztian's grandfather, Dimitar Vassilev, was in fact
the first outstanding gymnast in the family. Dimitar competed in
the 1952 Olympic Games with the Bulgarian team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
