<HEADLINE> Four of Seven UN Workers Taken As hostage in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Thursday announced that four of the seven United Nations military
observers taken as hostage in Abkhazia, Georgia had been released.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the noon brief, U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e
Silva said the negotiations for the release of the rest hostages
are under way.
</P>
<P>
Seven U.N. workers were taken hostage Wednesday near the line
separating Georgian government forces and the the territory of
Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. military observers from Uruguay, Sweden, Greece, the
Czech Republic and Switzerland had been taken along with a U.N.
doctor from Germany and an Abkhazian translator.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. group has just arrived by helicopter in the mountain
village of Azhara to deliver aid, when they were seized by
unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
There are 100 U.N. observers in Georgia to monitor the truce
between the Georgian Government and separatists in Abkhazia.
</P>
