<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing 100-Seat Jets Arouse Interest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Boeing 717-200 regional jet, a
new member of the Boeing plane family, today ended its four-day
showcase tour in China after a number of Chinese air companies
announced their intention to buy the aircraft for their fleets.
</P>
<P>
The 100-seat plane, designed for short-distance passenger
flights, has been the star attraction in seven air shows in
Beijing, Wuhan, Kunming and Xiamen since last Sunday, when the jet
arrived in Beijing from the United States.
</P>
<P>
A dozen Chinese airlines, including Wuhan, Yunnan, Shenzhen and
Xiamen air companies, have shown interest in the regional jets and
three of them have expressed their intent to purchase.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the jet successfully took off at Tianhe
International Airport in Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province, despite rain and visibility of less than 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
"We will buy five such planes," Cheng Yaokun, general manager
of Wuhan Air Company, told Ray Bracy, President of Boeing China
Inc.
</P>
<P>
"The regional jet costs less to fly, produces little noise, and
demonstrates fine safety performance. It will suit our company
that operates a great number of regional air services," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
In Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province where
air service is brisk, Duan Shenghu, flight engineer-in-chief with
Yunnan Air Company, attended two air shows featuring the jet in
one day.
</P>
<P>
"I have been responsible for purchase of regional planes for 15
years and I found the new Boeing regional jet has demonstrated
good capabilities and is well equipped," Duan said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, all 21 planes of his company are from the
Boeing airplane family. But the company is still short of planes
suited to short-distance flights within Yunnan Province, a
mountainous region which abounds in tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
Regional planes are those that have flight distance ranging
from 500 km to 1,500 km and have about 100 seats each.
</P>
<P>
In the next two decades, the world will need 2,600 planes each
with seats ranging from 80 to 120, but the need for big planes
like the Boeing 747 only stands at 930, according to specialists.
Therefore, developing regional planes featuring good capabilities
and low operation costs will become an important field where the
world's plane manufacturers will compete fiercely.
</P>
<P>
Research on Boeing 717-200 passenger planes started in 1995.
The first such aircraft was delivered in September this year. Air
companies from the United States and Europe have placed orders for
128 Boeing 717-200 planes, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Issue Antelope Conservation Declaration in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The international community took
the first bold step forward here today to coordinate efforts in
the fight against rampant poaching and smuggling of Tibetan
antelope, one of the world's most endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Seven countries jointly issued the Xining Declaration on the
Conservation and Control of Trade in Tibetan Antelope in this
capital city of northwest China's Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
The declaration describes in detail the responsibilities of the
countries concerned in protecting the endangered species and
controlling the trade of products made from the animal.
</P>
<P>
It calls for the governments of the countries to support this
move by providing necessary funds, technology and material aid. It
also urges the countries that process and sell cashmere products
to increase publicity about the conservation of Tibetan antelope.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was jointly issued by more than 80
representatives from government organs, non-government
organizations and experts from China, France, India, Italy, Nepal,
Britain and the United States, as well as personages from relevant
international conservationist organizations.
</P>
<P>
They were here to attend a three-day seminar on conservation
and control of the trade of Tibetan antelope which closed today.
</P>
<P>
The animal lives in the remote Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in
southwest China. Poachers hunted the animal for its fur, used to
make cashmere, which was smuggled to India and Nepal for
processing and later sold in Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been sternly cracking down on
poaching and smuggling of Tibetan antelope. It has also set up
nature reserves for the animal.
</P>
<P>
India, Nepal, France, Britain and Italy have also taken
measures to combat smuggling and wipe out the black market trade
of cashmere from Tibetan antelope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Cellared Spirits to Be Auctioned in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The world's oldest cellared
spirits -- still drinkable -- will be auctioned later this month
in Beijing, according to the China Guardian Auctions Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago archeologists discovered the yellowish alcohol,
dating back 154 years, sealed in four wooden containers at an
ancient bodega in northeast China. It was later determined to be a
tribute to the imperial family of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The London-based Guinness Book of World Records confirmed it as
the "oldest cellared alcoholic tribute" in the world on July, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists, who also unearthed liquor-making equipment
at the same site, described the smell of the ancient drink as "
pleasantly fragrant." They believed the airtight wooden containers
and constant temperature helped preserve the drink.
</P>
<P>
State authoritative tests on food and beverage showed that the
liquor meets the state standards for safe drinking.
</P>
<P>
Guardian, China's biggest auctioneer, will separate 100 kg of
the spirits into 50 lots for auction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum of Great Britain to Exhibit Chinese Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A four-month exhibition on
cultural relics from northwest China's Shaanxi Province will be
held in the Museum of Great Britain starting from October 20.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the world-famous museum to display
relics of a Chinese province.
</P>
<P>
A total of 140 articles of precious relics will be put on show.
The relics include terra-cotta warriors and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi Province is known as the "natural historical museum."
Xi'an, its provincial capital, was once the capital city of a
dozen dynasties and the start of the ancient Silk Road.  
</P>
</TEXT>
