<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Calls for Burden-Sharing Mechanism to Keep Malacca &AMP; Singapore Straits Clean, Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has called for the
establishment of a burden-sharing mechanism to keep the Malacca
and Singapore Straits clean and safe, taking a position that both
the coastal states and users of the straits should shoulder the
responsibility for providing maritime infrastructure for
navigational safety and for protecting the maritime environment in
the straits.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Communications and Information
Technology Yeo Cheow Tong made the point Thursday when he gave an
opening address at the two-day International Conference on the
Malacca and Singapore Straits, which is organized by the Institute
of Policy Studies (IPS) of Singapore and the International
Maritime Organization (IMO).
</P>
<P>
Yeo said it is inequitable for the coastal states to be
responsible for shouldering the responsibility to keep the straits
clean and safe.
</P>
<P>
Affirming that Singapore supports international cooperation in
the maintenance of the straits, Yeo said it will be useful to
develop an international agreed framework to share burdens in
maintenance of the straits and improvement of their infrastructure
to increase their capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Yeo made clear that his country is prepared to contribute a
fair share to a funding mechanism for the straits if there is an
international agreement to establish one.
</P>
<P>
However, the mechanism must not impede the passage of ships
through the straits, Yeo underlined.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, IMO Secretary-General William O'Neil told the
conference that he is concerned about the safety situation in the
Malacca and Singapore Straits, both of which he said are very busy
international waterways.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is possible to improve safety -- but only if we
consider the possibilities offered by the technology now available
and change some of the attitudes that still linger on from the
past."
</P>
<P>
"The most important is that one of the oldest traditions of the
sea -- that the authority of the ship's master should be paramount
-- may no longer be valid in a world that is becoming dominated by
new technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for firmer establishment of the concept that ships on
the high seas and outside territorial waters have an obligation to
obey rules imposed by international agreement.
</P>
<P>
On factors to be considered regarding positive vessel control,
O'Neil said the issue -- whether the coastal states or the ships
which use the system will pay the cost of the positive vessel
control-- must be discussed and properly addressed.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the need to address the liability issues if
something were to go wrong.
</P>
<P>
The conference is a follow-up of the first IPS/IMO conference
on the Malacca and Singapore Straits held in 1996 on the theme
"Navigational Safety and Control of Pollution in the Straits of
Malacca and Singapore: Modalities of International Cooperation."
</P>
<P>
More than 140 delegates from different parts of the world
attended the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
