<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing 100-Seat Jets Arouse Interest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Boeing 717-200 regional jet, a
new member of the Boeing plane family, today ended its four-day
showcase tour in China after a number of Chinese air companies
announced their intention to buy the aircraft for their fleets.
</P>
<P>
The 100-seat plane, designed for short-distance passenger
flights, has been the star attraction in seven air shows in
Beijing, Wuhan, Kunming and Xiamen since last Sunday, when the jet
arrived in Beijing from the United States.
</P>
<P>
A dozen Chinese airlines, including Wuhan, Yunnan, Shenzhen and
Xiamen air companies, have shown interest in the regional jets and
three of them have expressed their intent to purchase.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the jet successfully took off at Tianhe
International Airport in Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province, despite rain and visibility of less than 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
"We will buy five such planes," Cheng Yaokun, general manager
of Wuhan Air Company, told Ray Bracy, President of Boeing China
Inc.
</P>
<P>
"The regional jet costs less to fly, produces little noise, and
demonstrates fine safety performance. It will suit our company
that operates a great number of regional air services," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
In Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province where
air service is brisk, Duan Shenghu, flight engineer-in-chief with
Yunnan Air Company, attended two air shows featuring the jet in
one day.
</P>
<P>
"I have been responsible for purchase of regional planes for 15
years and I found the new Boeing regional jet has demonstrated
good capabilities and is well equipped," Duan said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, all 21 planes of his company are from the
Boeing airplane family. But the company is still short of planes
suited to short-distance flights within Yunnan Province, a
mountainous region which abounds in tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
Regional planes are those that have flight distance ranging
from 500 km to 1,500 km and have about 100 seats each.
</P>
<P>
In the next two decades, the world will need 2,600 planes each
with seats ranging from 80 to 120, but the need for big planes
like the Boeing 747 only stands at 930, according to specialists.
Therefore, developing regional planes featuring good capabilities
and low operation costs will become an important field where the
world's plane manufacturers will compete fiercely.
</P>
<P>
Research on Boeing 717-200 passenger planes started in 1995.
The first such aircraft was delivered in September this year. Air
companies from the United States and Europe have placed orders for
128 Boeing 717-200 planes, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
