<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Land Sale Attracts Lukewarm Response </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Lands
Department sold two government lots for a total of 706 million HK
dollars (90.5 million US dollars) at a public auction Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's biggest property developer, Cheung Kong (Holdings)
Ltd., won the bid for a 14,435 square meter site in rural Tin Shui
Wai for 555 million HK dollars (71.15 million U.S. dollars),
slightly higher than the opening price of 500 million (64.1
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The smaller lot of 2,267 square meters in the luxury
residential area of Repulse Bay attracted keen bidding with the
government offering it for 120 million HK dollars (15.38 million U.
S. dollars). It was sold to Fu Hop International Investment Co.
Ltd., a registered shell company, for 151 million HK dollars (19.
23 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Analysts had expected the two sites put on sale by the
government to raise around one billion HK dollars (128.2 million U.
S. dollars), and the outcome indicated that a recovery in the
property market still had some way to go.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the land developers are cautious but active
as the land auction was seen as a key test for the health of the
property sector, one of the mainstays of the Hong Kong economy.
</P>
<P>
But over the past six months property prices have edged upwards
by about 10-15 percent, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth land auction by the HK government. On April
20, the government's first land sale in nine months raised almost
1.5 billion dollars (192.3 million U.S. dollars), beating market
projections of 1.2 billion dollars (153.8 million U.S. dollars)
for three residential plots on offer.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended its land sales program at the end of
June last year in a bid to shore up sagging property prices that
had been hit hard by the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
