<HEADLINE> Most Russian Military Satellites Exhaust Service Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Up to 95 percent of the
communication satellites used by the Russian Armed Forces have
gone beyond their guaranteed service life, a ranking official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel General Yuri Zalogin, the Russian liaison troops chief,
said the number of military satellites will be cut in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
However, the general said that the current satellites in
service can cater to the communications of the military not only
inside Russia but also abroad, such as Bosnia and Yugoslavia's
Kosovo, where Russian troops are serving peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
Zalogin claimed that some communication satellites having a
three year service span have been doing fine for nine years and
longer, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
