<HEADLINE> China to Allow Easier Listing of High-tech Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to allow high-tech
firms easier access to the capital market in a bid to facilitate
technological upgrade of the state sector, a senior official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
A series of measures are being formulated by related government
departments for more high-tech firms to be listed on the nation's
two stock markets in Shanghai and Shenzhen, Zhou Zhengqing,
chairman of the China Securities Regulatory Commission, said in an
interview with Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that terms set for high-tech firms' access to
the stock market will be easier than in general practices, with
less requirements over the firms' balance sheets, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commission is considering to allow selected
firms currently listed on China's B-share market and Hong Kong
stock market to buy back their shares, he disclosed without
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that his commission will further improve efficiency
and strengthen supervision over the market so as to better serve
the needs of the reform of state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
