<HEADLINE> Beijing Continues Work to Control Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The national capital launched
the third stage of its anti-air-pollution campaign today by
proposing a set of 22 measures to reduce the volume of air
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has implemented a set of 46 measures to take air
pollution under control since late 1998, according to Zhao Yixin,
director of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Zhao told the press today that Beijing has made progress in
controlling air pollution thanks to effective measures to curb
local air pollution caused by coal burning, auto exhaust emissions,
and dust and suspended dirt particles.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sulfur dioxide density in the air in the past
nine months of this year fell an average of 25 percent from the
same period last year. The amount of nitride and oxide in Beijing'
s air remained at the same level as last year, even though the
city's number of automobiles has been increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The new measures will focus on the control of coal-burning and
auto-exhaust emissions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The city's industrial firms are all required to meet the city's
standards in environmental protection before the end of the year
2000, or they will be shut down, Zhao said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
