<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Meets Burundi Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni held talks with a delegation from the Burundi Peace
Process facilitation team in the southwestern district of Mbarara
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by Justice Mark Bomani of Tanzania called on
Museveni to brief him on the progress of the Arusha Peace Talks
aimed at bringing peace in Burundi, according to a press release
issued here by the President' s Office.
</P>
<P>
The delegation came to consult Museveni before the Burundian
factions resume their talks in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha
next Monday, considering that the peace process, initiated by
regional leaders, is now in its last stage.
</P>
<P>
The delegates have already held talks with Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi on the same issues and they are proceeding to
Bujumbura, the capital of Burundi.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether Thursday's death of former Tanzanian
president Julius Nyerere, the chief mediator in the Burundi peace
process, has any major negative impact on the forthcoming peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic violence between the minority Tutsi who dominate the
army and the majority Hutu culminated in the overthrow of the
elected government of President Sylvestre Ntibatunganya, a Hutu,
in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Burundi is still volatile and cases of
inter-ethnic killings are occassionally reported in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
