<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Issue Antelope Conservation Declaration in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The international community took
the first bold step forward here today to coordinate efforts in
the fight against rampant poaching and smuggling of Tibetan
antelope, one of the world's most endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Seven countries jointly issued the Xining Declaration on the
Conservation and Control of Trade in Tibetan Antelope in this
capital city of northwest China's Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
The declaration describes in detail the responsibilities of the
countries concerned in protecting the endangered species and
controlling the trade of products made from the animal.
</P>
<P>
It calls for the governments of the countries to support this
move by providing necessary funds, technology and material aid. It
also urges the countries that process and sell cashmere products
to increase publicity about the conservation of Tibetan antelope.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was jointly issued by more than 80
representatives from government organs, non-government
organizations and experts from China, France, India, Italy, Nepal,
Britain and the United States, as well as personages from relevant
international conservationist organizations.
</P>
<P>
They were here to attend a three-day seminar on conservation
and control of the trade of Tibetan antelope which closed today.
</P>
<P>
The animal lives in the remote Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in
southwest China. Poachers hunted the animal for its fur, used to
make cashmere, which was smuggled to India and Nepal for
processing and later sold in Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been sternly cracking down on
poaching and smuggling of Tibetan antelope. It has also set up
nature reserves for the animal.
</P>
<P>
India, Nepal, France, Britain and Italy have also taken
measures to combat smuggling and wipe out the black market trade
of cashmere from Tibetan antelope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Scores Breakthrough in Study of Mammal Origin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved a
breakthrough in the study of the origin of mammals with the
discovery of a large number of fossilized mammal bones dating back
some 100 million years in northeastern China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The fossils, including teeth, jawbones, vertebra and limbs,
belonged to a kind of small animal living in the Mesozoic Period,
said Zhang Pulin, who discovered these fossils along a 80-meter-
long and 50-meter-wide stratum in summer.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that it is quite rare to find mammal bones of the
Mesozoic Period, when the dinosaur dominated the world.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, the discovery will provide valuable
materials for the study of mammal origins, which will be the
hottest topic among the world's archeological in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Similar Mesozoic fossils have also been discovered in the
western region of Liaoning Province, also in northeastern China,
where Sinornithosaurus, believed to be the ancestor of birds, were
unearthed. But local archeologists believe these belonged to a
different family.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
