<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Habitats Crucial for Siberian Tiger Protection: Zoologists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We need to intensify international cooperation, set up natural
reserves, and ensure a smooth communication channel for the wild
Siberian tigers, so as to save the species from extinction," said
Dr. Dale G. Miquelle, Field Coordinator of the Siberian Tiger
Project under the WCS.
</P>
<P>
Zoologists point out that excessive hunting, de-afforestation
and the fast spread of housing areas have caused the rapid
decrease in the Siberian tiger population.
</P>
<P>
"In the past two decades, its number has decreased from over 80
to some twenty to thirty in the early 1990s," said Guan Guosheng
with the Heilongjiang WRI.
</P>
<P>
Some natural living areas suitable for the tigers still exist,
said Dr.Zhang Endi, in charge of the Asia Conservation
Communication Program. And the Central Government's efforts in
natural forest protection, together with the fact that there
remain over 300 Siberian tigers in the Russian border area, make
the protection possible.
</P>
<P>
Setting up a Sino-Russian natural reserve and an efficient
control network, and issuing related regulations will benefit the
protection, Dr. Miquelle said.
</P>
<P>
The investigation by the Wildlife Conservation Society, the
Hornocker Wildlife Research Institute, and the Heilongjiang
Wildlife Research Institute (WRI) in the province starting from
1998 reveals that now only between nine and 13 Siberian tigers
live in the forests of Wandashan Mountain, Laoye Mountain, and the
Changbai Mountains.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
