<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Returns Home After Surgery in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa returned home Thursday after recovering from a
successful heart surgery in neighboring Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Before quitting the Beirut's American University Hospital
(AUH), al-Sharaa issued a statement expressing his thanks to those
who have shown deep concern and care about his health, including
Lebanese president, prime minister and house speaker.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa, suffering from aortic dissection, was first admitted
to a private hospital in Damascus on October 3 with chest pains
during a reception for Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
After diagnosed, he decided to have an operation in the famous
AUH.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a team of seven doctors conducted the surgery which
was announced to be very successful.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beirut, Lebanese ministers, deputies and
celebrities flocked to the hospital to express their concern and
well wishes.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which is stationing a 350,000-member troop in Lebanon,
is a undisputed power broker in the country.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa, 59, has been foreign minister since 1984. He was
also a key figure in shaping Syria's foregin policy under
President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
His sudden illness sparked widespread concern for the current
peace process, which is widely anticipated to restart after
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak came to power in July.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was among the first to wish al-Sharaa a speedy
recovery, warying that the Syrian minister is an integral cog in
restarting peace talks with Israel, which broke down in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"We do wish him a successful treatment and a speedy recovery,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin has said.
</P>
<P>
Although the minister has left the hospital, it is unknown when
he will return to work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
