<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Scholar Commemorated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 Chinese and
foreign scholars gathered in this capital of southwest China's
Guizhou Province today to discuss the important role an ancient
Chinese thinker may have in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
At an international seminar that opened here today, scholars
from the United States, Japan, Russia, China and the regions of
Taiwan and Hong Kong will exchange views on the study of Wang
Shouren, widely known as Wang Yangming, a famous thinker,
philosopher and educator of the Ming Dynasty ((1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Tour to the ruins of the home of this ancient scholar has also
been arranged along with trade and investment promotion activities.
</P>
<P>
Wang was banished to Guizhou from the then capital city of
Nanjing, where he served as a senior official, for displeasing an
influential eunuch by speaking out from a sense of justice. While
staying in Guizhou, he trained many people by giving lectures
everywhere and cultivated a unique philosophical system.
</P>
<P>
His idea of stressing the unity of individual, society, nature
and heavenly laws can be equated to Western cultural values such
as equality and liberty, and his thinking has held an important
position not only in China for hundreds of years, but has also
influenced people in Japan and Korea, said one participant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs to Improve Freshness-Preservation Technology: Russian Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China needs to strengthen the
development and application of fruit and vegetable freshness-
preservation technology to ensure product quality and sharpen the
competitive edge in the global market, a renowned Russian
horticulture expert said today.
</P>
<P>
"Fresh-keeping facilities are essential to ensure that fruit
and vegetables retain their taste. This is the main appeal for
global customers," said Gudkovskl Vladimir Alexandrovich, director
of the I.V.Michurin All-Russian Research Institute of Horticulture,
one of the world's leading academic institution on horticulture
development.
</P>
<P>
The professor was airing his view at a workshop on agriculture
technology and know-how in Yantai, a port city in east China's
Shandong Province. The seminar was part of the International
Symposium and Exhibition on Fruit and Vegetable Processing
Technology and Industrialization, the first ever held in China,
which is runs through October 16.
</P>
<P>
The lack of advanced technology for keeping fruit and
vegetables fresh has long plagued the growth of the fruit and
vegetable processing industry in many developing countries in Asia,
including China, and has ruined 50 to 60 percent of their harvest
every year, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the world's largest fruit and vegetable
producers, with an annual production of hundreds of millions of
tons, but much of this is ruined every year due to poor fresh-
keeping facilities and technology.
</P>
<P>
The professor said that Russian research institutions and high-
tech enterprises are willing to come to China's aid with advanced
technology and facilities, and that exchange and cooperation in
this regard between the two countries is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Russia has developed freshness preservation and storing
technology for a variety of fruits. For example, it boasts a newly
developed storehouse equipped with advanced air-conditioning and
control systems which sharply reduce the amount of oxygen. Under
these conditions, apples can retain their look, taste, and
freshness up to 10 months after they are picked.
</P>
<P>
"I hope there will be more channels for technology talent of
both countries to cooperate in order to contribute to the
development of more advanced agricultural know-how," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
