<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cooperatives Erasing Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The supply and marketing
cooperatives (SMC) in China erased 370 million yuan in deficits in
the first eight months this year, basically holding the money-
losing trend in check.
</P>
<P>
SMC is a non-governmental farmers' organization. It is also a
key channel of commodity purchase and sales in China's rural areas.
It was born out of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the transition from a planned economy to a market-
orientated economy, the problems of cooperatives such as staff
redundancy, low-efficiency and lack of competitiveness have become
increasingly apparent.
</P>
<P>
The State Council issued a circular early this year urging an
immediate system reform to reverse the loss-making trend of
cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The All China Federation of Supply and Marketing Cooperatives,
the administrative body of grassroots cooperatives, has enhanced
efforts in reshaping money-losing enterprises by adopting the
shareholding system, acquisition and merger.
</P>
<P>
Li Dianhui, who is with the organization and attending the
fifth Asia-Pacific Cooperative Ministers' Conference being held in
Beijing, said that cooperatives are striving to make profits, and
"at least not to lose money in operation this year."
</P>
<P>
Although the downward trend is not reversed, the number of
money-losing enterprises were reduced by a large margin, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has a total of 30,000 cooperatives at all levels, with
cooperative members exceeding 180 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
