<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Levy Tax on Bank Account Interest in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China will begin to levy tax on
the interest of savings accounts on November 1, the government
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The 20-percent tax will be levied on the interest of all
Renminbi and foreign currency savings accounts that an individual
person opened in banks in China.
</P>
<P>
However, the interest that the savings accounts generated
before November 1 will be exempt.
</P>
<P>
The State Council announced here today that the government will
not levy tax on savings accounts exclusively for educational
purposes and other special savings accounts and funds that the
finance authorities has designated.
</P>
<P>
In August, the Chinese government activated the long-inactive
clause on interest tax in the Law on Individual Income Tax in a
move to stimulate consumption by residents.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Ministry of Finance said that the new tax is
like an interest rate cut by one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
The government believes that imposing the interest tax will
help take from the rich to pay the poor because about ten percent
of the population own 50 percent of the total savings deposits in
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Finance, the tax money will be
used to raise economic assistance for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, China's total savings deposits soared to 5,
910 billion yuan, compared to 1,520 billion yuan at the end of
1993.
</P>
<P>
However, China's retail prices have been falling for more than
20 consecutive months as economists rang alarms for deflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
