<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Mourns Death of Nyerere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday voiced his "great sadness" at the death of
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere, saying that he was "a
life-long friend and supporter of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Annan said in a statement, issued here, that "I heard with
great sadness last night of the death of Julius Nyerere, the
founder and first president of the United Republic of Tanzania,
and one of the architects of the Organization of African Unity."
</P>
<P>
"President Nyerere was one of the giants of the 20th century
African liberation movement," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"As a leader who brought his country to independence without
bloodshed, by uniting all the people in a single non-violent but
irresistible movement, he inspires a whole generation of Africans
struggling for freedom throughout the continent, in widely
differing countries and political contexts."
</P>
<P>
"Later he also set a fine example by renouncing power
voluntarily, and handing it on to his successor through an orderly
constitutional process," the statement said. "He fully earned the
nickname of 'Mwalimu', or 'Teacher', by which he was
affectionately known throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
"Both before and after leaving office, he gave unstintingly of
his strength and wisdom in the quest for African unity, freedom
and peace," the statement said. "Even in his last months he worked
tirelessly for a political settlement of the troubles in Burundi.
And he was a lifelong friend and supporter of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, his star shone well beyond the shores of Africa," the
statement said. "He had friends and admires all over the world. I
am proud to count myself among them, and I send my heartfelt
condolences to his family and people."
</P>
<P>
The former Tanzanian president died in a London hospital on
Thursday aged 77. He was diagnosed with chronic leukaemia last
year and admitted to St. Thomas's Hospital in London last month.
He went into intensive care on October 1, suffered a major stroke
last week and died at 0730 GMT on Thursday, when Annan, the first
black African to head the world body, is on a visit to London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
