<HEADLINE> HK Enhances Legislation Against Piracy, Counterfeiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
announced Thursday that copyright piracy and trade mark
counterfeiting offenses would be added into the Organized and
Serious Crises Ordinance (OSCO), subject to the approval of the
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
The offenses to be included are related to the making or
dealing with infringing copies of copyright works under the
Copyright Ordinance and infringement of trade mark rights and the
import or export of goods bearing a forged trade mark under the
Trade Descriptions Ordinance, the government said.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal underlines again our determination to protect
intellectual property rights," a government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
With the offenses specified under Schedule 1 to the OSCO,
Customs and Excise officers would have additional legal powers to
investigate piracy and counterfeiting offenses, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"These cover the production of material for investigation,
handling of crime proceeds and enhanced sentencing," he added.
</P>
<P>
If organized crime as defined in OSCO is involved, two
additional powers, confiscation of proceeds of offenses and the
removal of the right to silence, are available.
</P>
<P>
"With the additional legal tools, we will be able to deal more
severely with infringes," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"More legislative proposals are in the pipeline, for example,
prevention of bootlegging. The message is clear: piracy and
counterfeiting activities will not be tolerated in Hong Kong," the
spokesman emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
