<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southernmost Chinese Province Plans AIDS-Control Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- In order to prevent the spread
of AIDS, the island province of Hainan in southernmost China has a
plan to stop the virus from being transmitted through blood
donation channels, a major cause of AIDS infection on the island.
</P>
<P>
The plan underscores the importance of popularizing AIDS
education and knowledge about the ways sexually transmitted
diseases can be combated to the rural population. Related topics
will also be included in school textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Next year, five to six monitoring centers will be set up
offering regular examinations for venereal disease carriers, drug
addicts, and blood donator.
</P>
<P>
The province will also establish advanced AIDS consultations
and treatment and service centers as well as specialized medical
teams. The monitoring and instruction about the disease will be
given to communities who will be urged to set up an AIDS-control
network.
</P>
<P>
Hainan detected the first case of AIDS in 1991. Since then, 29
out of 140,000 people who received blood tests were found HIV
positive, and six of them died of AIDS. Experts believe that the
number of people in the province now contaminated has reached more
than 300.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
