<HEADLINE> China's Listed Township Enterprises Report Higher Profits than Nation's Average (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Interim reports of the 29
township enterprises listed on China's Shanghai and Shenzhen stock
exchanges indicate that their profits for the first six months of
the year outgrew the average for all domestic listed companies.
</P>
<P>
From January to June this year, these township enterprises
gained an income of 12.7 billion yuan from their main business
operations, up 51.9 percent from the same period last year, and 39.
43 percent higher than the national average for all listed
companies.
</P>
<P>
Their net profits hit 1.612 billion yuan, up 22.49 percent, and
17.65 percentage points higher than the average.
</P>
<P>
The reports also show that the listed township enterprises
further increased their money-making ability. In the first half
year, the average profits of these enterprises reached 55.5
million yuan, with the average ratio of assets and liabilities
standing at 38 percent. Six of them also have surpassed ten
percent in net-asset-return ratio.
</P>
<P>
To date, nearly 40 township enterprises have been listed
domestically since 1993 when the first township enterprise,
Guangdong Yuemeidi Electric Appliance A shares, was listed in
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
And some township enterprises has began to offer on overseas
stock exchanges. For example, the Guangdong Kelong Electric
Appliance has been listed in Hong Kong, and a porcelain company in
Guangdong Province is soon to be listed in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Township Enterprise Bureau under the
Ministry of Agriculture said that the listed township enterprises,
which lead in assets and profits in their respective domestic
sectors, are playing an exemplary role for other township
enterprises nationwide in their reform and development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
