<HEADLINE> Flags in Tanzania Fly at Half-mast for 30 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Thursday ordered flags to fly at half-mast for 30
days in memory of late leader Julius Nyerere who died of leukemia
at the age of 77 in a London hospital in the morning.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Tanzanian government has suspended all
sports or cultural activities indefinitely in the country.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam, national anthems were
played by TV or radio stations on and off to remember Nyerere who
led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Flags of both ruling and opposition parties as well as foreign
embassies were seen flying at half-mast.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Chama Cha Maendeleo na Demokrasia (CHADEMA),
Bob Makani, said he would send heartfelt condolences to President
Mkapa for the premature and sad demise of Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition party Civic United Front (CUF) has also
sent condolences to Mkapa, saying the party joins millions of
Tanzanians in mourning Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
"I can't believe that Mwalimu (teacher) Nyerere is gone
forever," said Alhaj Salum Katungunya, who is one of the early
founding members of the then Tanganyikan African National Union
(TANU) and ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Culture in the Ministry of Education and
Culture, Daniel Ndagala, said that the suspension decision has
been made to enable all Tanzanians to mourn their fixtures following the gover
ent's
suspension of sports activities.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere was an ardent sports fan and took part in various
sports activities. His most favorite game was "bao".
</P>
<P>
During his presidency, Nyerere's notable achievement was
Tanzania's participation in the 1980 Africa Cup of Nation Finals
in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from neighboring Kenya said that
President Daniel arap Moi said that flags in his country will fly
at half-mast for four days beginning Friday following the death of
Nyerere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
