<HEADLINE> China's Listed Township Enterprises Report Higher Profits than Nation's Average (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But despite their superb economic performance, township
enterprises still face many obstacles in their attempts to become
listed, and the total number of listed township enterprises
account for only about 4 percent on the domestic stock market.
</P>
<P>
"This is not conducive to township enterprises reform, nor to
their competition with state-owned enterprises on an equal footing,
" he said, noting that such a small percentage of listed
enterprises does not jibe with the status of township enterprises
in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, and especially since late 1970s,
township enterprises have witnessed remarkable development and now
constitute the main part of the rural economy, representing almost
half of the country's industrial sector and a pillar of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The National Bureau of Statistics indicates that in 1998,
rural businesses realized an added output value of 2.2186 trillion
yuan, making up 27.9 percent of the nation's gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
At the same time, these businesses contributed one-fifth of
all national tax revenues and 34.8 percent of the country's total
exports.
</P>
<P>
China's township enterprises have maintained a momentum of
steady growth so far this year. From January to August, they
reported a total output value added of 1.6213 trillion yuan, up 16.
8 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
 The official called for more attention to be paid to the
importance of listing township enterprises and more support in
this regard. 
</P>
