<HEADLINE> Speed Up Research on Electric Vehicle: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Prof. Lun Jingguang from
Qinghua University said that China should speed up its research on
electric vehicles to protect the country's environment and promote
consumerism.
</P>
<P>
Lun was speaking at the 16th International Electric Vehicle
Symposium, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Lun pointed out that electric vehicles produce no exhaust
emission -- one culprit responsible for China's worsening air
quality.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, surplus electricity generated in the evening can be
used for battery charging for electric vehicles, said Lun.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China generated 270 million kwh of electricity, 60
million of which were surplus and can be used for battery charging
for 12 million electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Lun noted that the research on hybrid vehicles and fuel cell
vehicles is now a trend, adding that the hybrid vehicle, with its
advantages of having both an internal-combustion engine and
batteries, will have a larger market in China in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1998, the Toyota Motor Corporation has sold 30,000 hybrid
vehicles. Other major auto makers, such as General Motors, are
also doing research on them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
