<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Chief to Visit Saudi Arabia Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen is due in Saudi Arabia next Tuesday for talks with
Saudi leaders on regional security and the situation in Iraq,
western diplomats said in Riyadh on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay in the Gulf kingdom, Cohen will meet
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz and his counterpart Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz, the
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will attach great emphasis on the situation in Iraq and
on how to restore order in the region, they added. But they did
not go into details.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has 5,000 troops in a military base in Saudi Arabia
and the U.S. warplanes regularly take off from the base to enforce
the no-fly zone in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones in northern and southern Iraq were imposed by
the U.S.-led western alliance following the 1991 Gulf War, sparked
by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies claimed that they carved out the no-fly
zones to protect the Kurds in the north and Shiite Muslims in the
south from Baghdad's possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's visit to Saudi Arabia is part of his seven-nation
regional tour, which will also take him to Kuwait, Bahrain, the
United Arab Emirates, Egypt, Jordan and Israel, according to the
Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Saudi defense chief is scheduled to
visit Washington early next month for talks with U.S. leaders on
boosting political, security and defense cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
