<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pentagon Reviews Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States must
improve its electronic combat power for future wars in the light
of the Yugoslav army's ability to maintain its air defenses in the
face of heavy NATO bombing, U.S. Defense Department officials told
Congress Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Air Force RC-135 electronic eavesdropping planes and Navy
and Marine Corps EA-6B electronic attack aircraft were stretched
thin against a formidable Serb air defense, Defense Secretary
William Cohen and Joint Chiefs Chairman Henry H. Shelton said in
an "after-action review" of Operation Allied Force, the 78-day
NATO campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Serbs successfully husbanded most of their best air defense
weapons, prompting NATO commanders to keep allied attack planes at
higher altitudes, thus reducing their effectiveness against ground
targets.
</P>
<P>
"We need to find innovative and affordable ways to exploit our
technological skills in electronic combat to bring greater
pressure to bear on a future enemy's air defense system," Cohen
and Shelton said in a joint written statement summarizing the
findings thus far in an ongoing Pentagon study of the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and Shelton presented the 18-page statement at a Senate
Armed Services Committee hearing on the war. A fuller study,
headed by Cohen's and Shelton's top deputies, is due in January
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
