<HEADLINE> GA President Mourns Death of Nyerere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The president of the
54th General Assembly (GA) session, Theo-Ben Gurirab, Thursday
voiced his "deep personal sadness" of the death of the former
Tanzanian president, Julius Nyerere, saying that "the African
people as a whole have lost an ardent pan-Africanist."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Guirab, also the Namibian foreign
minister, said, "It is with deep personal sadness that I learnt of
the passing of Mwalimu (Teacher) Julius K. Nyerere, first
President of the United Republic of Tanzania, venerable world
leader and one of Africa's most charismatic and respected elder
statesmen."
</P>
<P>
The former president died overnight in London at the age of 77,
after suffering from leukemia.
</P>
<P>
"I, too, was a beneficiary of Mwalimu's political tutelage and
of Tanzania;s generosity; they provided me a free haven when I
fled my own country Namibia, in 1962, to escape South Africa's
brutal colonialism in Namibia," the GA president said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Tanzanian people have lost the father of the nation, the
courageous leader of their independence struggle and the architect
of the United Republic of Tanzania," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The African people as a whole lost an ardent pan-Africanist, a
man of high principles, a man of self-abnegation and the champion
of Africa's self-determination, liberation and independence," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Without Dr. Nyerere's firm guidance and steadfast support, the
struggle for liberation, particularly in southern Africa, would
hv
have been more difficult and divisive within the ranks of the OAU,
th Non-Aligned Movement and other freedom-loving forces in the
world," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
