<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Learning a Lot from Climate Experience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A series of climate experiments
designed to improve weather forecasts show that rising hot-air
currents over the Tibetan plateau and the South China Sea are
stronger than once thought.
</P>
<P>
Top China Meteorological Administration (CMA) official Wen
Kegang was quoted as saying that hot air masses rising over the
plateau are bigger than expected.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists determined that the air waves include a tropical
squall line that can cause waterspouts over the South China sea.
</P>
<P>
"Analysis and understanding of these results will help us
better understand atmospheric motions and the rules governing the
interactions of related spheres and layers," Wen stressed.
</P>
<P>
Wen pledged to get to the bottom of climate shifts affecting
storms in the Asian monsoon region and in the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The research was initiated in 1996 and carried out largely in
the summer of 1998. Using modern technology and large fields of
observation, the meteorologists did atmospheric-ocean-hydrological
tests in the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, the South China Sea, the
Huaihe River and the Taiwan Straits, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Research also revealed the special characteristics and
complexity of the plateau's atmospheric structure, Wen said in his
latest report on the experiments. These projects had financial
backing from the country's Ministry of Science and Technology and
the National Natural Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The four experiments, involving 29 provinces, municipalities
and key industrial cities, also show China's advanced
meteorological level and ability to coordinate scientists at home
and abroad to undertake large atmospheric experiments.
</P>
<P>
"In this way, China is expected to make contributions to global
atmospheric research and to break through in the field," CMA's
experts said, adding that some 100 foreign experts jointed hands
with more than 500 senior Chinese meteorologists to do the tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Action to Protect Antelope in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING October 14 (Xinhua)-- An international jointed action
aimed at protecting the endangered Tibetan antelope is expected to
kick off soon, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The antelope face the threat of extinction because of massive
illegal hunting. The antelope are in high demand for their
underwool, used to make shawl known as "shahtoosh."
</P>
<P>
"Such a step has been in the works for years, as the illegal
poaching in China, the country of antelope's origin, and the
illicit manufacturing and trade of shahtoosh in processing and
consuming countries, defy the common wish of mankind to protect
wildlife," a leading Chinese forestry official was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The root of the poaching is that the process and trade of
shahtoosh still exists in certain countries and regions as
poachers, processors and traders can obtain huge profits soaked in
the blood of Tibetan antelope," said Ma Fu, deputy-director of the
State Forestry Administration(SFA).
</P>
<P>
India-controlled Kashmir is the world's first and largest area
for the manufacturing of shahtoosh shawls. Most of the raw
materials for these luxury items has been smuggled from Tibet,
said one SFA expert.
</P>
<P>
Most of the shawls are sold in Europe. Since 1994, hundreds of
shahtoosh shawls have been seized or confiscated in France,
Belgium, the United States, Britain, Italy and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
