<HEADLINE> EU to Pay Partly for Chiluba's Shuttles for Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
release some 2.9 million U.S. dollars to Zambia to offset part of
the payments for President Frederick Chiluba's diplomatic shuttles
to mediate peace in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
This was stipulated in the memorandum of understanding signed
between EU Ambassador to Zambia Jochen Krebs and Zambian Permanent
Secretary of Finance Ministry Boniface Nonde here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be released within weeks, an EU official said.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Nonde said that while his government
is trying very hard to further the mediation process as quickly as
possible, the peace process may take longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
"This is mainly due to the complexity of the issues at hand and
the number of parties involved," the Zambian official explained.
</P>
<P>
After signing the memorandum, Krebs told the press that the
Zambian government approached to EU on the financial assistance
for Chiluba's peace missions.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was mandated by the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to mediate a peaceful solution to the war in the
third largest African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
