<HEADLINE> Local Records in China Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China is carrying out a
nationwide revision of local records, aiming to faithfully mirror
historical events.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 historians and compilers have been involved
in the largest project of the kind in 20 years, renewing some 4,
000 volumes of chronicles, said Shan Tianlun, an official
responsible for directing the national job.
</P>
<P>
"Accuracy and documentary value are our top requirements for
the job, so that the history can be truly reflected," Shan
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The entire work includes 6,000 volumes of historical books with
a total six billion words.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition to display achievements of the massive effort
will soon be on view at the Museum of the Chinese Revolution,
which is located east of Tian'anmen Square in central Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Records compilation and revision have a history of over 2,000
years in China. This activity has not only enriched the country's
cultural heritage, but also provided reference for today's
policymakers, Shan said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has always paid attention to the local
chronicle revision work, even though it was suspended during the "
Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976), he said, adding that special
institutes have been set up in provinces, cities and counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
