<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Cellared Spirits to Be Auctioned in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The world's oldest cellared
spirits -- still drinkable -- will be auctioned later this month
in Beijing, according to the China Guardian Auctions Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago archeologists discovered the yellowish alcohol,
dating back 154 years, sealed in four wooden containers at an
ancient bodega in northeast China. It was later determined to be a
tribute to the imperial family of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The London-based Guinness Book of World Records confirmed it as
the "oldest cellared alcoholic tribute" in the world on July, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists, who also unearthed liquor-making equipment
at the same site, described the smell of the ancient drink as "
pleasantly fragrant." They believed the airtight wooden containers
and constant temperature helped preserve the drink.
</P>
<P>
State authoritative tests on food and beverage showed that the
liquor meets the state standards for safe drinking.
</P>
<P>
Guardian, China's biggest auctioneer, will separate 100 kg of
the spirits into 50 lots for auction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
