<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Round-Table Talks Held in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- All the pro-peace agreement
parties in Northern Ireland are holding round-table talks for the
first time in London as part of the review chaired by former U.S.
Senator George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
The round-table talks followed separate discussions on Thursday
morning involving the Ulster Unionists, Sinn Fein and the Social
Democratic and Labour Party.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at the talks venue in Lancaster House in London,
Ulster Unionist Leader David Trimble and Sinn Fein President Gerry
Adams both said no progress had been made over the previous days.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell moved his review of the process to London on Tuesday
to intensify discussions between the parties in a private
location.
</P>
<P>
Adams said the atmosphere between the parties had improved
while Trimble said he was still committed to breaking the
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
When the London-based talks started, a spokesman for Mitchell
said they were expected to end on Thursday, but Mitchell would
come back to Belfast next week.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Mitchell has taken the parties away from
Stormont in Belfast since the review began last month.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks started on Tuesday, Mitchell said the review
was entering a "crucial phase". 
</P>
</TEXT>
