<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Mourns Death of Nyerere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF) Thursday mourned the death of the former Tanzanian
president, Julius Nyerere, saying that "the world has lost a
gentle and wondrous man."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the U.N. agency said that he was "a
man who consorted with kings and mingled with the masses in equal
egalitarian harmony."
</P>
<P>
"The death of President Julius Nyerere is one of those moments
which makes time stand still," the statement said. "It's the
silencing of a voice which, uninterrrupted for five decades, never
abandoned principle, never abandoned purpose, never abandoned
vision."
</P>
<P>
He "will always remain in memory as that slender, diminutive
figure of irresistibly infectious chuckle, with a mind so sharp as
to cut to the heart of every argument, but a tongue so kind as to
soothe the soul of every adversary," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout his life, Mwalimu (Teacher) ever-managed that
combination of intellect and generosity which made him so beloved
as the leader of his country," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement sang highly of Nyerere's contribution to the
victory over colonism, to the building of his nation, to the
struggle against apartheid, and to the contemporary quest for
peace in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The contribution and "his litany of accomplishments" "touch
everyone on the African continent," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere died in a London hospital on Thursday aged 77. He was
diagnosed with chronic leukaemia last year and admitted to St.
Thomas's Hospital in London last month. He went into intensive
care on October 1, suffered a major stroke last week and died at
0730 GMT on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
