<HEADLINE> UN's Council Elects Five New Non-permanent Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Member States on Thursday elected Bangladesh, Jamaica, Mali,
Tunisia and Ukraine as the five new non-permanent members to the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The five new members which replace Bahrain, Brazil, Gabon,
Gambia and Slovenia will take their two-year terms beginning on
January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is composed of five permanent members
with the power of veto and 10 non-permanent members that each
serves two-year terms.
</P>
<P>
Five non-permanent members that will remain on the Council for
another year from next January 1 are Argentina, Canada, Malaysia,
Namibia and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council deals with international crises involving
armed conflict.


nnnn
