<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Try to Set Refugee Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAMPERE, Finland, October 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
leaders will gather here on Friday to hold a two-day special
summit in bid to harmonize the 15 member states' immigration and
asylum policies among others for years to come.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders at the justice and home affairs council will
focus on various projects including a common visa system, stricter
EU external border controls, more police cooperation, a
European-wide immigrant fingerprinting database and coordinated
rejection of asylum seekers.
</P>
<P>
In the past, a lack of trust between EU governments has often
hampered efforts to get agreement on common justice and home
affair rules. Even while the leaders look for harmonized tone in
Tampere to try to discourage as many as people as possible from
seeking asylum within the EU borders, they will still face the
problem of what to do with those people who are allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
For years, those EU members which have traditionally received
large number of refugees, led by Germany, have called for the EU
to put in place a system to "share out" asylum seekers more evenly
between the 15 EU countries. However, it is always a hard
question.
</P>
<P>
Data shows that a decade of anti-immigration measures, such as
visas, fines on airlines, reduced welfare, detention and
deportation, have done little to halt thousands of people seeking
a safe livelihood in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Some ten years ago, 308,040 asylum seekers arrived in Europe.
It was 334,230 in 1998. In fact, blocking access and making life
unberable for asylum seekers did not stop hundreds of thousands of
Yugoslavs, Afghans, Somalis, Angolans, Sri Lankans, Iraqis,
Iranians, Kurds and others. They often claim that they suffered a
second round of persecution inside the European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
However, current EU president Finland has expressed their
resolve to take the opportunity in Tampere to "develop the Union
as an area of freedom, security and justice in the next
millennium, acting in a responsible and influential manner at the
global level". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
