<HEADLINE> Top Cyprus Immigration Officials Involved in Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Two top civil servants in
Cyprus' Immigration Department were suspended from services
Thursday pending investigations for illegal supply of temporary
residence and work permits to foreigner.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, Cyprus' Interior Minister
Christodoulos Christodoulou said that in a letter Wednesday,
Police Chief Andreas Angelides asked for the suspension of
Christodoulos Nicolaides and Nicos Vakanas of their services in
Immigration Department.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said the suspensions will be in force for three
months, unless police investigations are concluded earlier.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Angelides said that preliminary investigations
have shown that the two might be involved in cases concerning the
supply of illegal temporary residence and employment permits.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary at the Interior Ministry, Andreas
Panagiotou, will temporarily replace Nicolaides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus police last week launched an emergency probe into
allegations that police officers are involved in flesh-trading
and are being paid to supply fake residence permits for foreign
women in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has acquired a bad reputation for importing female
cabaret dancers who are then allegely forced to work as
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
Angelides has vowed that any officers found guilty of
involvement in the alleged scandal would face the full penalty
under law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
