<HEADLINE> Talks Fail to Make Zimbabwean Doctors Back to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The two-day meeting between the
striking doctors and parliamentarians of Zimbabwe failed to yield
positive results on Thursday as the doctors laughed off
persuasions to return to work.
</P>
<P>
The doctors thanked the members of parliament for their efforts
in mediating but told them, "Regrettably the doctors' general
meeting resolved to continue the industrial action because the
minimum demands have not been met."
</P>
<P>
Vice-President of the Hospital Doctors Association Tatenda
Mawire said the doctors wanted a written statement resolving their
grievances as a matter of urgency.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Speaker of Parliament Edna Madzongwe said the
Parliamentarians had tried their best to find the solution as they
were concerned with the health situation in their constituencies.
</P>
<P>
She said, "We have not lost hope, we are still going to see
what we can do to pressure for a bigger portion for the Health
Ministry when the budget is announced next Thursday."
</P>
<P>
"People are now tired of burying their relatives. Our interest
is to see them going back to work and we will keep on persuading,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The doctors went on strike three weeks ago and vowed to
continue until their demands for salary and allowance increase
were met.
</P>
<P>
The strike had paralyzed the country's health delivery system
with patients being turned away and wards attendants were
instructed not to admit new cases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zimbabwe Human Rights Association said in a
statement that the government should put the health of the
citizens above everything.
</P>
<P>
"Before the doctors went on strike people were dying of curable
diseases because of the unavailability of drugs. Today they are
dying of neglect and the state of affairs cannot be tolerated," It
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
