<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Hails Merger of French and German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin hailed on Thursday the planned merger between the French
aerospace group Aerospatiale-Matra with its German counterpart
DASA as a triumph of European construction.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder in Strasbourg, Jospin said that the future Franco-German
aerospace group, European Aeronautic, Defense and Space Company
(EADS), will be one ``powerful tool for the construction of a
strong and unifying Europe mastering fully its future.''
</P>
<P>
He also said that the success of the rapprochement between the
two countries' aerospace industries shows the ``irreplaceable role
of the Franco-German cooperation as the locomotive of European
construction.''
</P>
<P>
Aerospatiale-Matra and DASA announced on Thursday that they
planned to merge in the first half of 2000 to create Europe's
number one aerospace company and the world's third largest with an
annual sales of 21 billion euros (22.6 billion U.S. dollars) and a
work force of 89,000.
</P>
<P>
The move is apparently aimed at strengthening Europe's stand in
the world aerospace and defense market which is dominated by the
United States companies such as Boeing.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also called on other European Union (EU) partners to
``join as soon as possible this demarche'' by allying with the new
group, which he said ``has the vocation to facilitate the tie-up''
with aerospace industries of all EU countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Jacques Chirac was delighted to know
this agreement, which ``fully inscribes itself in the perspective
of a European defense under construction.''
</P>
<P>
``Faced with the constitution of international groups of very
great dimension, notably in America, it should become a key move
to ally European forces,'' said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the future group will have its shareholders
mainly based in Europe and would be ``given the means for
ambitious strategic and industrial projects and for creating
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the merge will strengthen the development of
the Airbus, ``which will find a new push to embrace the challenge
of tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
Aerospatiale-Matra and DASA are the main shareholders of Airbus
consortium, with the British Aerospace and the Spanish aerospace
group CASA being their partners.
</P>
<P>
The French government will hold 15 percent of the shares of the
future EADS group, while the Lagardere group, which is the owner
of Matra, will hold 11 percent and unidentified French share
holders 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
DASA will hold another 30 percent, while the remaining 40
percent of the shares will circulate in stock markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Military Govt Rejected to Commonwealth Summit: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's military
government would not be allowed to attend next month's
Commonwealth summit in Durban, South African President Thabo Mbeki
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted Mbeki as telling
journalists in Cape Town that Commonwealth secretary-general Emeka
Anyaoku had yet to approach him about the matter.
</P>
<P>
However, the Commonwealth took a decision when it met in
Zimbabwe in 1991 that the organization itself was committed to,
and should defend, democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
It was on that basis that Nigeria, in the aftermath of the
executions of Ken Saro Wiwa and other Ogoni activists, was
suspended from the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
"I would imagine for the Commonwealth to be consistent in its
views, clearly, I don't think it would allow that a military
government should be represented at the forthcoming heads of
government," Mbeki said in reply to whether Pakistan would be
suspended.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was deposed in a
bloodless military coup on Tuesday after he tried to axe army
chief General Perven Musharraf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
