<HEADLINE> Africa Must Recommit to Peace to Honor Nyerere: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki said Thursday that the best way to pay tribute to
African statesman and late Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere was
for the continent's people to re-commit themselves to the cause of
peace, stability and a better life for all.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki described Nyerere's death as loss for the "continent of
Africa as a whole", South African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere was a pillar of strength to oppressed people all over
the world and was admired for his wisdom, his intellect and
integrity, Mbeki was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere served as a source of great inspiration to efforts
towards Africa's rebirth.
</P>
<P>
"He was one of the wise sons of Africa who guided our journey
towards placing Africa in her rightful place in the world."
</P>
<P>
At the height of his career, Nyerere had dedicated himself to
the upliftment of his people and remained committed to justice and
equality.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said the national flag would fly at half mast countrywide
from Friday to Tuesday in memory of Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
On whether he would attend Nyerere's funeral or send a
representative, Mbeki said: "Hopefully there will not be an
engagement, here or elsewhere, which would make it difficult for
us to attend. It would be a very good thing if the president of
South Africa could attend." 
</P>
