<HEADLINE> Britain Says No Formal Chile Request to Free Pinochet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Thursday it was
not true that it had received a formal request from Chile for the
release of detained former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet on
humanitarian grounds.
</P>
<P>
"It's completely untrue," a Reuters report quoted a Home Office
spokeswoman as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the Home Office confirmed that Chilean President Eduardo
Frei had sent a confidential letter to Prime Minister Tony Blair
last week, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"The Chilean president sent a letter to the prime minister last
week on October 7, but it was confidential and we cannot comment
on its contents," the Home Office spokeswoman said in tehr report.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes told a Chilean
radio station on Thursday that a document had been handed in to
Britain's Home Office, formally asking Home Secretary Jack Straw
to let Pinochet go on humanitarian grounds.
</P>
<P>
Chile's government has long argued that Britain should release
Pinochet and stop the extradition sought by Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinoceht, 83, was house-arrested in October of last year in a
London hospital while he was recovering from a minor back
operation.
</P>
<P>
A Spainish judge accused him torture in the latter part of his
1973-1990 rule and wanted to try him in Spain.
</P>
<P>
A Britaish court ruled out last week that Pinochet should be
extradited to Spain to face the charges. Pinochet was not in the
court to hear the ruling, as required by British law, because of
his frail health and old age.
</P>
<P>
The former commander-in-chief of Chile's army is currently
under house arrest in a hired mansion in the south-west suburb of
London. His lawyers had lodged an appeal to a higher Britain
court. He is expected to keep on fighting against the extradition
proceedings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
