<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is concerned and disappointed at the decision by the
United States Senate not to ratify the Comprehensive Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT), the Foreign Ministry said in a statement
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It (The South African government) believes that this
development undermines the gains already achieved by the
international community in nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria had hoped that the U.S. Senate would achieve
bipartisan consensus to enable the White House to ratify this
Treaty and join the international community in reinforcing both
the legal force and moral authority of the CTBT, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the U.S. Senate to reconsider its view.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the only country in the world which acquired
nuclear capacity but later destroyed it.  
</P>
