<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Presses for Resumption of Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Special Presidential Envoy
to Cyprus Alfred Moses Thursday held talks with Turkish leaders in
a bid to outline a formula for the resumption of the deadlocked
Cyprus talks.
</P>
<P>
Moses met with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, discussing
ways of resolving the longstanding Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
Turkey maintains a 35,000-member troop in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island through a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation formula, but the peace talks between the two sides have
been stalled since 1997.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is the staunch supporter of Turkish Cypriots, who
proclaimed a breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in
1983 that is recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Moses' visit is seen as a follow-up to the discussion between
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Ecevit in September, which created
an atmosphere of relative optimism that a negotiation formula
satisfactory to the Turkish side could be outlined.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Ecevit, Moses said that they had
had "a friendly and constructive" discussion.
</P>
<P>
Turkish sources said that Moses' efforts were aimed at
outlining a formula that would bring Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Denktash rejects face-to-face talks as long as he is not
granted political status equal to that of Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Ankara was Moses' first leg of a three-nation trip and he will
travel on to Greece and Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
