<HEADLINE> Two RAF Aircrew Killed in Jet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Two RAF aircrew were killed when
their Tornado GR1 jet crashed in a remote farmland on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plane, on a routine training flight from RAF Lossiemouth in
Scotland, came down between Ingoe and Kirkheaton, about 16
kilometers from Newcastle.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses described how the unarmed aircraft veered from its
course and exploded in a "horrendous fireball" 500 yards from farm
buildings.
</P>
<P>
A RAF spokesman said only one aircraft had been involved in the
accident although eyewitnesses reported seeing a light aircraft
flying very low in the area seconds before the Tornado came over.
</P>
<P>
RAF Communications Officer Tony Parrini said: "As far as we
know at this time, there were no other aircraft in the vicinity
and there was certainly only one aircraft involved in this
incident. The aircraft was not carrying any weaponry at the time
of the incident."
</P>
<P>
But Gale Brown, 37, who lives about 500 meters from the crash
scene, described seeing another plane in the area.
</P>
<P>
"A few seconds before the RAF aircraft came over there was a
little passenger plane which came over, very low indeed," she
said. "I was giving a riding lesson at the time and was warning
the rider to get ready to steady the horse with the noise.
</P>
<P>
"We get jets over all the time, but the little passenger plane
was like a stranger in the camp. It looked like a 10-seater
aircraft with windows down the side. The next thing we saw were
two RAF aircraft come over, and then one of them come down," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
