<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes Republicans for Nuke Treaty Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday blasted the Senate's rejection of the nuclear test ban
treaty as "partisanship at its worst."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the East Room of the White
House, Clinton said the vote revealed a "new isolationism" from
the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
"In recent days, members of the congressional majority have
displayed a reckless partisanship that threatens America's
economic well-being and now, our national security," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Even more troubling are the signs of a new isolationism among
some of the opponents of the treaty," he added, citing the refusal
of the Republicans to pay the U.S. debt to the United Nations and
refusal to adopt proposals to stem tide of global warming.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reiterated that the U.S. will continue to retain its
moratorium on nuclear weapons test and will support the nuclear
test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to pursue the fight against the spread of
nuclear weapons. And we will not -- we will not -- abandon the
commitments inherent in the treaty and resume testing ourselves.
I will not let yesterday's partisanship stand as our final word on
the Test Ban Treaty," Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
On a largely party line vote, the Senate defeated the treaty
late Wednesday by 51-48. The United States thus became the first
nuclear power to specifically reject the treaty on ending nuclear
weapons testing.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was approved by the U.N. General Assembly in 1996
and has been signed by 154 countries. Clinton signed the treaty
in 1996 and sent it to the Senate for ratification in September,
1997.
</P>
<P>
The pact will not take effect until it is ratified by all the
44 member countries of the Geneva-based Conference on Disarmament.
It has been ratified by 26 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
