<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Successful JMC Meeting on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday extended his welcome to the successful holding
of the first full meeting of the Joint Military Commission (JMC)
in Kampala, the Ugandan capital, on October 11-12.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in a statement issued here by his spokesman, said, "He
is encouraged that the representatives of the parties to the
conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo have extended in
writing guarantees of security for United Nations personnel and
property to be deployed in the DRC (Democratic Republic of
Congo)."
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations looks forward to working with them towards
the restoration of peace in that country," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The delicate peace process in Congo (K) was boosted this week
when the warring parties met and agreed on basic measures to help
prevent a new round of fighting.
</P>
<P>
The participating representatives gave formal security
guarantees for U.N. peacekeepers who will monitor compliance with
the peace deal and made substantial progress on defining the
territory controlled by each of the forces and the number of
troops they have on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"The security guarantees given at Kampala will allow the United
Nations to proceed with the deployment of Military Liaison
Officers and civilian personnel to rear and field headquarters in
the DRC, and the early dispatch of a Technical Survey Team which
will review conditions on the ground," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan reiterated his support for the efforts by the
Organization of African Unity to help implement the Lusaka
ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Annan highly commended the Governments of South Africa, Uganda
and Zambia for "their generous contributions in cash and in kind
to the functioning of the Joint Military Commission," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to present a report on the issue to the U.N.
Security Council on the enlarged presence in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that subject to authorization by the Security
Council, this will lead to the deployment of a United Nations
peacekeeping operation," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The war broke out in Congo (K) in August 1998 and sucked at
least five other African nations, with Uganda and Rwanda backing
rebel groups and Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia all supporting
Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
A team of 90 U.N. observers is to prepare the ground for the
deployment of a 500-strong peacekeeping force, but its deployment
in the conflict zones had been delayed because of continuing
insecurity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
