<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Strengthens Industrial Standardization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has set up a
documentation center to strengthen the national standardization
with more than 250,000 national, regional and international
standards for industries and service sector.
</P>
<P>
The center has provided the Kenya Bureau of Standards with
documents on standards and trade in the international network,
said Phillip Okundi, Managing Director of the national standards
body, in a message observing the World Standards Day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, standardization began with the birth of Kenya Bureau
of Standards in 1974. Over the past years, the bureau has
developed more than 2, 000 Kenyan standards with the participation
of technical experts from both public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
To promote the standardization, the bureau has invested heavily
in the necessary human and infrastructural needs to provide
assistance to manufacturers and service industry for offering
quality goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The bureau as Kenya's standards flag bearer has introduced a
certification marking scheme nationwide to encourage
standardization in industry. Manufacturers whose products meet
the Kenya standards are issued with permits to use the
standardization mark.
</P>
<P>
Okundi said his bureau now operates the Diamond Mark of
Quality, a guarantee of product quality to consumers, adding that
firms with proven quality record are issued with permits to use
the Diamond Mark after a series of stringent quality assessments
by the bureau.
</P>
<P>
To date, 78 firms in the country have been issued with permits
to use the Diamond Mark of Quality on their products, which is
recognized in the two East African sister states of Uganda and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In the next millennium, Okundi said, his bureau is under
obligation to enhance Kenya's industrial and commercial
competitiveness through promoting of metrology, establishment and
use of standards, testing and quality management.
</P>
<P>
He called upon all Kenyans to join the rest of world in
utilizing standards as the key tools for staying abreast of
technology-driven business development, especially in globalized
free trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
Kenya should put the issues of human safety, environment and
national economy at the forefront to facilitate the development
of standards faster in order to meet the emerging market needs,
Okundi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
