<HEADLINE> Brutal Act against U.N. Staff Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. General
Assembly on Thursday condemned brutal acts against U.N. personnel
in the field of operations, while mourning the killing of three
U.N. personnel this week.
</P>
<P>
Assembly President Theo-Ben Gurirab said the loss of three
staff within a 24-hour period underscores the often difficult and
dangerous conditions under which U.N. personnel serve.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the day's plenary session began, Gurirab said
the death of the three people brings to 13 the number of civilian
staff killed this year alone, indicating a sharp increase in
attacks on U.N. staff.
</P>
<P>
He called for effective measures by governments and parties in
armed conflicts to ensure the safety and security of U.N.
personnel and other humanitarian workers.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight-year-old Bulgarian national Valentin Krumov of the
U.N. Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo was shot dead in
Pristina Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Burundi next day, 52-year-old Chilean national and U.N.
Children's Fund Representative Louis Zuniga along with Saska von
Meijenfeldt, a 34-year-old Dutch national and World Food Program
Logistics Officer were killed in a road ambush.
</P>
<P>
They were part of an interagency team on an assessment mission
of humanitarian needs in a camp for displaced persons. Seven
Burundian nationals also lost their lives and several others were
seriously injured in the tragedy Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly observed a moment of silence for Krumov, Zuniga
and Meijenfeldt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
