<HEADLINE> HKSAR Telecommunications Chief Talks of Telecom Asia 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- While Telecom '99 in Geneva is
still going on, Hong Kong of China is doing its best to make
preparations for ITU Telecom Asia 2000, said an official of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed last June in Geneva by the
International Telecommunication Union (ITU) and the Chinese
government, Hong Kong was designated to host the most important
telecommunications event in the Asia-Pacific history on December
4-9, 2000.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the venue of Telecom '99, Anthony
Wong, director-general of HKSAR Telecommunications and the
Telecommunications Authority, briefed journalists about Hong
Kong's preparations for the first-ever ITU telecom event to be
held in China.
</P>
<P>
Wong expected that the major event would attract over 40,000
visitors. As the gateway to China's mainland and Southeast Asia
and the major financial and commercial hub in Asia, he said, Hong
Kong will surely make Telecom Asia 2000 a great success.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that Hong Kong is a city with boundless
energy and drive and English is widely spoken and is able to
provide quality services with its excellent communications and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the exhibition venue, Wong said that over 64,000
square meters of gross function space are now available at the
Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center after new extension was
completed in 1997. The center provides restaurants, banking and
postal facilities, and on-site hotels.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is well developed with 75 percent of households
covered by broadband services, Wong said. There are over 3.5
million mobile phone users and over 135 ISPs serving over 800,000
dial-up accounts in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
