<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey: New Era in Turco-EU Ties to Be Opened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said on Thursday that the
thorny ties between Turkey and the European Union can enter "a new
era" if Ankara's candidacy of EU membership is officially approved
at the Helsinki Summit in December.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Turkish Foreign Ministry in the day said
Turkey has once more been declared a candidate for EU full
membership in a recent report of the EU Commission.
</P>
<P>
"If all the recommendations of the commission are approved at
the EU summit in Helsinki, that is if Turkey is granted an
official candidate status with all its components, a new era will
be opened in the relations between Turkey and the European Union,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit has said that the report
is "encouraging" and constitutes "a positive development"
following his meeting with President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the report is not binding and that
"we should wait for the outcome of the Helsinki Summit."
</P>
<P>
In a press conference here on Thursday, EU Commission
Representative in Ankara Karen Fogg played down speculation that
despite its present positive approach, the EU will obstruct
Turkey accession process, putting forward new conditions in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Fogg said that speculation on a timetable for the start of
accession talks can be very dangerous, stressing that Turkey
itself has asserted that it will not consider it a discrimination
if its accession talks do not start simultaneously with the other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
During the summit in Luxembourg in December 1997, the EU
decided to invite Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Five other nations -- Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and
Slovakia -- were put on a slower negotiating track by the
15-nation union. And Turkey, a 34-year applicant, was left
completely in the cold.
</P>
<P>
The result of the summit was disappointing for Turkey, but "it
was not an obsession for Turkey and we will not treat it as an
event that will have an impact on the course of Turkey," said
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem at that time. Enitem


14/10/99 20:27 GMT

NNNN
04:38 04:38 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
