<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Declares 30 Days of Mourning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Thursday announced that his nation will mourn 30
days for the death of the former head of state Julius Nyerere who
died of leukemia earlier in the day in a London hospital.
</P>
<P>
With all flags lowered to half-mast for 30 days and all sports
or cultural activities suspended indefinitely, the grief-stricken
Tanzanians are eagerly waiting for the arrival of their founding
father's body.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi, with Mkapa as the National
Chairman, will hold a special meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has not decided where or when the
funeral will take place, but President Mkapa announced on national
TV that the father of the nation will be given all respects he
deserves.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British government has offered a special plane
to transport the body of Nyerere to Dar es Salaam, BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
It said special prayer for Nyerere is scheduled to take place
at the Westminster Cathedral in London, and all well wishes and
Tanzanians living in Britain and neighboring countries will have a
chance to pay their last respects to Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city, Deputy Chairman of opposition Tanzanian
Labor Party (TLP), Augustine Mrema, said that he hoped that
Tanzanians would forget their political, ideological and religious
and even tribal differences during the mourning period.
</P>
<P>
"We should foster national unity in this difficult time just as
Mwalimu himself was a man of unity in all his lifetime," he said,
adding that "we expect that people would not use the death of the
Father of the Nation for the benefit of their political parties,
religions and social settings."
</P>
<P>
Several workers of the Tanzania Standard Newspapers (TSN),
publishers of Daily News, sobbed an wiped tears as the
announcement was made exactly at mid-day by President Mkapa, who
was flanked by Vice-President Omar Ali Juma and Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye.
</P>
<P>
Condolence messages started to pour in and many official
engagements were postponed following the death of Nyerere, who was
admitted to the St. Thomas' Hospital on September 24 and was in
and out of coma before died at 0730GMT Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, addressed as Mwalimu or "teacher" throughout Africa,
was respected for his intellect and integrity. He retired as
president in 1985 after 24 years of office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
