<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Multilateral Talks Before Syrian-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Thursday reiterated that
the multilateral talks, as part of the Middle East peace process,
should not be resumed until all bilateral peace negotiations,
especially on the Syrian track, are restarted.
</P>
<P>
If the Syrian-Israeli and Lebanese-Israeli peace negotiations
"witnessed a resumption and progress, then the multilateral talks
could likewise see progress," Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks after meeting with visiting
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley, who arrived here
Wednesday on a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"We are no die-hard rejectionists," Moussa said, explaining
that the agreed land-for-peace principle and the drive for
reconciliation are "the crux of the matter."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel have got
back on track early September with the signing of the Sharm
el-Sheikh Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
But talks on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks on the return of
Syria's Golan Heights and Israeli troops' withdrawal from south
Lebanon have been stalled since 1996 after hardline Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took power.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Golan from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war
and carved out a border zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with the
claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak's election as Israeli prime minister in May
rekindled hope for realization of comprehensive peace in the
region because he pledged to make peace with Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He has fulfilled his promises to some extent by reviving the
peace drive with the Palestinians. But there have been no notable
signs so far for the resumption of talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral talks, kicked off in 1992, were designed to
tackle issues such as disarmament, water, Palestinian refugees,
the environment and economic cooperation, but they came to a halt
in 1996 after Netanyahu came to office.
</P>
<P>
Daley is on a regional tour, which has taken him to Jordan, the
Palestinian self-rule areas and Israel, and he will travel on to
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
