<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: France, Germany Merge Aerospace, Defense Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany announced
Thursday in Strasbourg that the French aerospace and defense group
Aerospatiale-Matra and its German counterpart DASA will merge in
the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The merger, which is the first of such scale in Europe in the
aerospace and defense field, also signals the acceleration of a
process of building a single European aeronautics, defense and
space industry.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder announced the merger plan in the eastern French
city to show their firm support to the consolidation of the
European aerospace and defense industries, which they consider to
be the key to the construction of European defense.
</P>
<P>
The future merged group, European Aeronautic Defense and Space
Company (EADS), will be the world's third largest aerospace group
after the U.S. Boeing-McDonnell Douglas and Lockheed-Martin and
will have an annual sale of 21 billion euros (22.6 billion U.S.
dollars) and a work force of 89,000.
</P>
<P>
It will be headed by Jean-Luc Lagardere, president of the
council of supervision of the Aerospatiale-Matra, and Manfred
Bischoff, president of DADA.
</P>
<P>
The merger also opens the way for alliance with other European
aerospace and defense groups, including the Spanish CASA and the
British Aerospace, which are partners in the Airbus consortium,
the most important component of EADS.
</P>
<P>
Based in Paris, Frankfurt and Amsterdam, EADS will be the
world's second largest group in civil aviation after Boeing, the
first in helicopter making and satellite launching, and the second
largest in missile and satellite making after the U.S. Raytheon
and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Jospin said that EADS will be a powerful
tool for building a strong and unifying Europe who is the master
of its own future.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Schroeder said that the Franco-German
alliance will push forward the construction of an independent
military force in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The merger will put an end to three years of disagreement
between Aerospatiale and DASA, which failed to strike a deal on
merging the missile and satellite parts of their groups in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It will also pave the way for the building of an independent
Airbus group which will ally with the British Aerospace and
Spanish CASA.
</P>
<P>
The future EADS will have 80 percent of the shares of Airbus,
while British Aerospace will have 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the building of a single Airbus group have
come into a deadlock for one year because of disputes over
powersharing between the four groups involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
