<HEADLINE> Russian Spokesman: Moscow-NATO Ties Remain Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Thursday that its
ties with NATO remain frozen and Moscow is not taking part in any
joint activities with NATO aside from the peacekeeping operations
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The readiness of NATO to better take into account Russia's
interests and concerns regarding fundamental European and
international security issues may become a prerequisite for the
unfreezing of relations between Russia and NATO," Russian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry's statement came in response to "recent
attempts by representatives of various NATO structures to increase
contacts with Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's ties with NATO was frozen following the beginning of
NATO air raids on Yugoslavia on March 24. All contacts with NATO
have since been halted other than consultations on the
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Russia has 3,600 troops in the Yugoslav province as part of 40,
000 multinational peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that another condition would be the
willingness of the alliance to strictly observe the understandings
in the framework of the Russia-NATO Founding Act.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has taken notice of the statement concerning the need
to improve NATO-Russia relations made by the alliance's new
Secretary General George Robertson shortly after his appointment,
Rakhmanin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
