<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Concerned Over U.S. Refusal to Nuclear Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Thursday voiced
serious concern over the refusal by the U.S. Senate to ratify the
comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty, saying it marked a
worrisome trend in U.S. activities recently.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is "disillusioned and seriously concerned" about the
Senate's decision, which "deals a serious blow to the whole system
of agreements in the field of nuclear disarmament and non-
proliferation, especially as far as the non-proliferation treaty
is concerned," Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted 51-48 Wednesday to throw out the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). More than 150 countries have
signed the deal but it cannot go into force unless all 44 nuclear-
capable states, including the United States, ratify it.
</P>
<P>
"What causes deep concern is the quite definite trend that can
be seen in U.S. activities of late," the Interfax news agency
quoted Rakhmanin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Along with its decision not to ratify the test ban treaty, the
U.S. has adopted a new law on ABM defense systems, issued new
threats about export controls and taken other steps that "
destabilize the foundations of international relations", the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it was the U.S. that took "the most active part"
in the preparation of the CTBT and was also the first country to
sign it, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said, U.S. President Bill Clinton's
statement that Washington will keep to its moratorium on nuclear
tests, which is being observed by all five nuclear powers, did not
pass unnoticed by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Moscow, sticking to the treaty, "regards it
as its duty to take into consideration the consequences of the (
Senate's) decision on the treaty for security and safety all over
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry also blasted the Senate decision,
saying it set "a dangerous precedent with far-reaching
consequences."
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the decision "may cause an imbalance in the
entire system of control over the nonproliferation of nuclear arms
and nuclear technologies," Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
