<HEADLINE> Japan, Palestine to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Thursday agreed to
enhance bilateral cooperation to boost the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached the agreement during a 25-minute
meeting at the Japanese prime minister's official residence, a
Japanese government official said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi reiterated his commitment to "extending economic
assistance and playing a political role...given the importance of
Palestinian stability and prosperity in moving forward the Mideast
peace process," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here earlier in the day to attend a two-day
meeting of donors to Palestinian, thanked Obuchi for Japan's
economic assistance and other contributions for Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also revealed his decision to open an
office in Japan. Palestinians had a representative office in Tokyo
under the Palestine Liberation Organization, but closed it in June
1995 due to financial problems.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official said Obuchi hailed Arafat for his "
tenacious" efforts in the peace process, and expressed the hope
that both Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will
continue to lead "negotiations toward an agreed target of
realizing a final agreement in September 2000."
</P>
<P>
Arafat told Obuchi that he is "optimistic," and reiterated the
Palestinian authority holds the right to declare independence next
year, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
