<HEADLINE> Romanian Ships Allowed to Enter Yugoslav Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Romanian convoy consisting
of 12 ships entered Yugoslavia's territorial waters this week, the
local daily newspaper Curentul quoted the director of the Drobeta
NFR River Navigation Company Dumitru Vidoe as saying.
</P>
<P>
They are the first Romanian cargo ships to enter the Yugoslav
territory since the Kosovo conflict broke out.
</P>
<P>
The convoy bound for Novi Sad to load grain in the Romanian
Black Seaport of Constanta.
</P>
<P>
Romanian shipowners and river operators blocked the Danube
River in August to draw the attention of the Yugoslav and Romanian
authorities to the difficulties the naval companies were facing,
which were caused by the delay of restoring traffic on the river.
</P>
<P>
Romanian river fleet operations have sunk into a poor state
after NATO's airstrikes destroyed three bridges in Yugoslavia,
blocking the traffic on the Danube in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Romanian naval companies registered huge losses from the
blockage, since almost 85 percent of the Romanian river
commodities freights are bound for Hungary, Austria and Germany
through the Yugoslav Danube River's waters. Millions of tonnes of
goods from and to Central Europe piled up in the Romanian ports by
the Danube and the Constanta Port.
</P>
<P>
Romania has the largest river fleet in Europe, with 1,100 non-
propelled vessels of 1,000-3,000 tonnes and over 180 tugboats of
500-4,600 horse power. International river traffic contributes 75
percent to the Romanian river's fleet capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
