<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Expects U.S. Senate to Change Position on CTBT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Thursday voiced hope
that the Republican-controlled United States Senate could
reconsider and ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
"We expect the issue will be discussed again in the United
States in consideration of the atmosphere of global support for
the CTBT," the South Korean Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea hopes the U.S. Senate's rejection of the treaty is
not the final position of the United States, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope the United States, which has played a leading
role in the global non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and arms
reduction, will continue to do so," added the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, South Korea ratified the treaty, which is
aimed at curbing the spread of nuclear weapons by banning the
detonation of nuclear bombs underground, at sea, in the atmosphere,
and in space.
</P>
<P>
In a roll call vote Wednesday, the U.S. Senate failed to ratify
the treaty by a 51 to 48 vote. The Clinton government signed the
treaty in 1996 and sent it to the Senate for ratification in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
Explaining its decision, the Senate said a total ban on nuclear
tests would undermine the U.S. ability to upgrade nuclear weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The CTBT was approved by the U.N. General Assembly in 1996 and
has been signed by 154 countries. It will take effect when it is
approved by all 44 member nations of the Geneva-based Conference
on Disarmament. To date, 26 states have ratified it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
