<HEADLINE> Chretien Unveils Job and Maternity Initiatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien unveiled job and maternity initiatives Wednesday at the
on-going 36th parliament session.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pledged to finance the creation of 1,200 new
research positions at Canadian universities.
</P>
<P>
The country's academic community is hailing the newly spelled
plan, which is expected to cost 60 million Canadian dollars (about
41 million U.S. dollars) next year and 180 million (about 122
million U.S. dollars) by its third year.
</P>
<P>
The money is intended to support rising young academic stars
for the ambitious goals announced in the Speech from Throne
Tuesday for the country's millennium development based on
knowledge industry.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also announced that by January 1, 2001, the
maternity leave would be extended from the current six months to a
full year under the unemployment-insurance system.
</P>
<P>
Both initiatives were mentioned in Tuesday's Throne Speech,
which officially opened the current session of parliament.
Chretien were just adding details to the general ideas outlined in
the speech. 
