<HEADLINE> Two Japanese City Banks Announce Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Sumitomo Bank and Sakura Bank,
two of Japan's major commercial banks, announced an agreement
Thursday to form a broad-based alliance by April 2002 to create
the world's second largest bank.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached a basic agreement on business integration,
which we assume will be achieved by April 2002," Sakura Bank
President Akishige Okuda said in a joint press conference with
Sumitomo Bank President Yoshifumi Nishikawa.
</P>
<P>
"The new bank intends to be one of the world's top commercial
banks," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two have combined assets of 99 trillion yen (about 820
billion dollars), second only to the one to be formed by a planned
alliance among Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank (DKB), Fuji Bank and the
Industrial Bank of Japan (IBJ).
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo and Sakura's announcement came one week after Asahi
Bank and Tokai Bank said they would set up a joint holding company
in October 2000.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March 2000, the end of the current business year
for both banks, Sumitomo and Sakura will own shares in each other,
the two banks said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of full integration, the banks will form a partnership in
some areas of retail and wholesale banking, and in international
services, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two banks plan to close 151 domestic outlets and 32 offices
abroad by March 2002 and will trim 9,300 jobs by March 2004, they
announced.
</P>
<P>
They also said nonperforming loans, a major factor behind the
banking industry shakeup, will be put to an end by March 2002.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Bank, based in Osaka, western Japan, has 51.5 trillion
yen (about 428 billion dollars) in assets with about 15,000
employees, while Tokyo-based Sakura Bank has 47.2 trillion yen (
about 392 billion dollars) in assets with a workforce of 16,300.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Bank and Sakura Bank have acted as the chief source of
funds for Japan's two major competing corporate groups-- Sumitomo
and Mitsui. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
