<HEADLINE> Greece to Send Joint Team to Georgia for U.N. Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece decided Thursday to send
a joint diplomatic and military team to Georgia to assist in
negotiations for the release of five U.N. observers kidnapped by
unknown gunmen in the breakaway region of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Deputy Defense Minister Dimitris Apostolakis said
Thursday that the Greek team would leave Thursday for Georgia with
the aim of ensuring that no harm comes to the U.N. observers,
including a Greek officer, whose name is George Kopanos, an
artillery captain.
</P>
<P>
Apostolakis said that Greece had asked the Georgian government
to be informed in advance about any plans it may have to try and
release the observers by force.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Nikos Athanasakis said at
a press briefing that Greece hoped force should not be used to try
and release the observers.
</P>
<P>
The observers from Greece, Uruguay, Switzerland, Sweden and the
Czech Republic were reportedly kidnapped by nine gunmen 75
kilometers northeast of Sukhumi together with their Russian
interpreter after their helicopter came under fire Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou Wednesday condemned
the kidnapping and said that Greece were watching this matter
closely. 
</P>
