<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Franco-German Locomotive at Work Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- After experiencing 10 months of
lukewarm relations, France and Germany are again finding
themselves playing the joint role of a locomotive pulling forward
the train of Europe's political, economic and defense integration.
</P>
<P>
By putting together the strategically key aerospace and defense
industries, Paris and Berlin are renewing their relations of
mutual trust and returning to the same bed after a deviation by
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in trying to woo the British lady.
</P>
<P>
The merger between Aerospatiale-Matra and DASA is a decisive
step by Europe in allying its aerospace and defense industries to
get free from the dominance from an all-powerful United States.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the historic plan in Strasbourg, French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin invited all the European partners of France
and Germany to join the "demarche" as soon as possible, which he
said is aimed at quickening the building of a European defense.
</P>
<P>
He said that the merger is a big step in the integration of
Europe's civil and military aeronautic industries and is the fruit
of a common political will of the governments of France and
Germany to reinforce their industrial and defense ties.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that the merger itself will serve as a
locomotive for Europe and will allow it to fare better in the
global competition, especially facing the other side of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that Germany has been criticized for having not
made cooperative ties with France strong enough.
</P>
<P>
Relations between France and Germany came into trouble when the
German government announced last winter that it would abandon its
nuclear industry, which is closely linked with France's nuclear
processing plants.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also disputed deeply about the financing of
the European Union institutions, with Germany intending to cut its
contributions and criticizing France for giving too little.
</P>
<P>
The French Socialist government was annoyed by a joint
manifesto co-signed in June by Schroeder and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair on seeking the so-called "Third Way" of
neo-liberal social-democracy in Europe, about which the French
feel uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
But London's long prior strategy of sticking to an alliance
with the United States, including in the field of defense
industry, has maintained the distance between the European
continent and the British isles.
</P>
<P>
In September, Schroeder began to mend his ties with France by
inviting Jospin to Berlin and explained his understanding of
relations with France, which he said were of "an affair of heart."
</P>
<P>
The series of failure suffered by the Social Democrats in a
number of regional elections and the European election also taught
a lesson to Schroeder, forcing him to seek a change of his image
at home by turning left again.
</P>
<P>
As a minor sign of renewing alliance, Germany is also
supporting French opposition to the lifting of embargo on British
beef products by the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
