<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Thailand's Efforts to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
Thursday a loan of 400 million U.S. dollars in support of the Thai
government's efforts to improve the efficiency and effectiveness
of public sector services.
</P>
<P>
The Public Sector Reform Loan focuses on improvements in
revenue and expenditure management, human resource management,
decentralization, participation, transparency, and accountability,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure that recovery is swift and sustainable, Thailand has
to focus on improving competitiveness, encouraging the private
sector, strengthening governance, enhancing social justice and
protecting natural resources," said World Bank Thailand Country
Director Jayasankar Shivakumar.
</P>
<P>
"Had the importance of improving governance been recognized
earlier..., the current economic crisis could have been avoided,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to making the public sector more effective and
responsive, this reform program also helps Thailand achieve its
goal in alleviating poverty, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank loan is at the bank's standard interest rate
for Single Currency Loan-based U.S. dollar loans with a maturity
of 15 years, including a 3-year grace period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
