<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Political Situation Takes A Dramatic Turn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's political
situation has taken a dramatic turn early Friday as the army led
by coup leader General Pervaiz Musharraf declared the state of
emergency throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said that the state of emergency,
declared two days after the bloodless coup, came as the apparent
failure of hectic efforts to form an interim or a caretaker
government which deserves the army's trust.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf, who is also chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff Committee and the Army Chief, is reported to have called a
meeting of corps commanders discussing the future plans Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The enforcement of the state of emergency in the country seems
to be the last option by the army under the present circumstances.
</P>
<P>
According to what the army called "A Provisional Constitution
Order" issued in the wee hours of Friday, the state of emergency
was enforced throughout Pakistan with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf has assumed the office of the Chief Executive
of Pakistan, and the whole of Pakistan shall come under the
control of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's constitution has been suspended and
the national and provincial assemblies have been dissolved, but
the president of Pakistan shall continue in office.
</P>
<P>
The order also announced the dismissal of the prime minister,
the federal ministers, the ministers of state, advisors to the
prime minister, parliamentary secretaries, the provincial
governors, the provincial chief ministers, the provincial
ministers and advisors to the chief ministers.
</P>
<P>
The order, however, did not mention the duration of the state
of emergency. It is still not clear whether this is a temporary
arrangement which will be followed by general polls.
</P>
<P>
Responses from various political parties and organizations are
still awaited.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the growing rift between the government and the
army over various issues of national importance, the army staged a
coup Tuesday evening which overthrew the 31-month-old government
of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif first assumed his premiership in November 1990 and was
ousted from his office in April 1993. He was elected the top
executive of this south Asian nation in February 1997 with an
overwhelming mandate.
</P>
<P>
However, he failed again to complete the
constitutionally-stipulated five-year tenure of office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
