<BODY>
<HEADLINE> League and Sponsors Happy with Worthington Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Football League insist the
Worthington Cup is not being devalued by some teams' decision to
play with lesser-known players in their sides.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United, Arsenal and Chelsea all fielded relatively
unknown players in their third-round ties. But League director of
communications Peter Rowe is adamant the "vast majority" of teams
are playing at full strength.
</P>
<P>
He added that sponsors Bass Breweries are very pleased with the
competition. "We recognize that teams have squad systems in this
day and age, so we wouldn't necessarily term it as an under-
strength team," said Rowe.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly don't think the competition is being devalued.
When you look at some of the teams last night the vast majority of
clubs competing take the competition very seriously.
</P>
<P>
"There are a few clubs who operate a squad system, and we have
to adapt to that in modern football. But there were some great
games. We believe attendances are holding up - in the last round
attendances were up two percent, and that was a positive sign."
</P>
<P>
Rowe believes the promise of a UEFA Cup place for the winners
of the Worthington Cup has been another incentive for teams to
field their strongest sides. "There is an all-round increase in
the number of games, so we have to try and adapt and in doing that
we have reasonably well achieved it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For the majority of clubs it is a great opportunity for them
to get into Europe. Ask Tottenham - if it wasn't for this
competition they wouldn't be playing in Europe. So George Graham
would be a good person to ask about the pluses of winning the
Worthington Cup.
</P>
<P>
"The other benefit is the great legitimate distribution of
wealth. By using the cup we can distribute money to smaller clubs.
Bournemouth went to West Ham where there was a crowd of 22,000 and
they got 45 percent of the gate. That will help them enormously."
</P>
<P>
Punters and bookmakers, though, are upset by the policy of some
Premiership teams in the Worthington Cup. Bookies William Hill
believe under-strength sides in the competition have affected the
compilation of odds and punters' choices.
</P>
<P>
"Punters don't know whether the teams they are backing to win
individual games or the Cup itself are taking the competition
seriously, which discourages them from having a bet," said Hills
spokesman Graham Sharpe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
