<HEADLINE> Wales on Mark for New Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of
Wales have decided they want Mark Hughes as their new manager -
but they won't admit it!
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night they would only announce that they had
decided who they want and would open negotiations with his club in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Bizarrely, the FAW were unwilling to actually name Mark Hughes
as their target, despite weeks of open discussion about the 35-
year-old's appointment.
</P>
<P>
Hughes is the man the FAW want after a full council meeting in
Cardiff decided on their target, and they will approach
Southampton for his services.
</P>
<P>
But the technicality of Hughes already being under contract to
the Saints stopped FAW secretary general David Collins officially
naming the former Manchester United legend after the meeting at a
Cardiff hotel.
</P>
<P>
But the key issue is that the FAW have decided who they want
and they have not considered delaying an approach, or considered
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
Southampton will be asked for their permission to approach the
man who has been caretaker boss of Wales for the past two matches,
and talks between Hughes, his advisors and the FAW will take place
over the next few days before a formal announcement is made.
</P>
<P>
Collins said after the meeting: "The FAW council has met and
decided to open negotiations with regard to a national team
manager, and following a successful conclusion of those talks we
hope to be able to make an announcement shortly.
</P>
<P>
"Those negotiations will take place over the next few days and
we hope to be able to announce the successful applicant.
</P>
<P>
"We will now be talking to the individual and the club
concerned, we need to talk to the chairman and to get his
permission to approach the player and take it from there. We will
be offering the player a contract to become our national team
manager," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
