<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Return of Macao to End China's History of Humiliation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Opium War (1840-1842) brought China more than 100 years of
disgrace and humiliation. Emboldened by the fall of Chinese power,
the Portuguese colonialists instigated a series of crimes
violating China's territory: forcing the shut-down of Chinese
Customs, refusing to pay taxes and rent to the Chinese government,
levying taxes on Chinese people in Macao, and expelled Chinese
government agencies from the island.
</P>
<P>
In 1887, Portugal deployed military forces to take over Macao
and its nearby islands, and forced the government of the Qing
Dynasty to sign the unequal Sino-Portuguese Treaty of
Reconciliation and Trade to legitimize its occupation.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese struggles against this invasion and
colonialism have never ceased on the island, ranging from
demonstrations to the assassination of a Portuguese governor.
</P>
<P>
Chinese history began a new era when the People's Republic of
China was founded 50 years ago. The new government announced it
would never recognize the unequal treaties that the foreign powers
had forcibly imposed on China.
</P>
<P>
On April 13, 1987, the governments of China and Portugal signed
a joint declaration to confirm that the Chinese government would
resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao on December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Macao, which weathered all the hardships of Chinese history, is
about to embrace a new life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay Reports Growth in Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay's exports have
registered 1.22 billion U.S. dollars during the first seven months
of this year, up 26.8 percent compared with the same period of
1998, official resources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports amounted to 1.84 billion dollars, leading to
a deficit of 623 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) remained the major trade
partner of Uruguay, accounting for 45.4 percent of the country's
exports and 41.7 percent of its imports.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is composed of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Bolivia and Chile as associate members. 
</P>
