<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislator Describes Visit to U.S. as Good Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The current visit to the
United States by the Chinese parliament delegation is a good start
for exchange of visits between the legislative bodies of the two
countries, a senior Chinese legislator said at a press conference
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Jianhui, head of the delegation of the National People's
Congress (NPC) of China, said this visit has established channels
of communications and laid a good foundation for the future
exchanges and communications between the parliaments of China and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The NPC delegation arrived here Monday for a goodwill visit at
the invitation of the U.S.-Chinese Inter-parliamentary Exchange
Group of the U.S congress.
</P>
<P>
This is the first official invitation extended to a Chinese NPC
delegation from the U.S. congress in a decade.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the U.S. congress has established such an
exchange group and has decided to set up a relationship of
exchanges with the Chinese NPC shows the importance that the U.S.
congress attaches to its relations with the Chinese parliament,
Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, member of the NPC Standing Committee and chairman of the
NPC Foreign Affairs Committee, called for joint efforts to promote
mutual understanding and development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"The NPC, which also attaches great importance to its relations
with the U.S. congress, is ready to work with the U.S. parliament
to this end," Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
He said the NPC delegation exchanged views with the U.S.
congress on the issues of common concern and bilateral relations "
in a friendly, cooperative, serious and frank atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
"Such talks have enhanced our mutual understanding and
increased our common ground," Zeng said, "we have become closer
and closer."
</P>
<P>
The two sides, though different on some issues, have reached an
agreement to promote the development of Sino-U.S. relations in a
sound and stable manner, Zeng noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
