<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Direct Marketing Sales to Outpace Overall Sales Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The total direct marketing
sales in the United States will exceed 2 trillion U.S. dollars in
five years, continuously outpacing overall sales growth in the
country, a new study said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, commissioned by the U.S. Direct Marketing
Association (DMA), reveals that business-to-business direct
marketing sales are projected to comprise almost half of all
direct marketing sales by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Between 1994 and 1999, the direct marketing sales to consumers
in the country increased at a compound annual growth rate of 8.5
percent per year, compared to 5.5 percent annual growth in total U.
S. consumer sales.
</P>
<P>
Business-to-business sales increased 11 percent per year during
the period, versus a 5.6 percent annual growth rate in overall
business-to-business sales.
</P>
<P>
The total U.S. direct marketing sales grew from 970 billion
dollars in 1994 to estimated 1.53 trillion dollars this year. The
study forecast its total sales will reach 1.67 trillion dollars in
2000 and 2.34 trillion dollars by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Direct marketing is an interactive system of marketing that
uses one or more advertising media to effect a measurable response
at any location.
</P>
<P>
Direct mail, print advertising, catalogs, telephone, personal
computer, cable television as well as other media deliver the
information that is necessary for the consumer to make an informed
buying decision.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, direct response and spending will reach
176.5 billion dollars in 1999, comprising 57 percent of total U.S.
advertising expenditures of 309 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The growth in jobs attributed to direct marketing continues to
outpace overall U.S. employment growth, the study said.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, between 1999 and 2004, direct marketing
industry employment is expected to grow at an annual rate of 4.2
percent, more than four times of the overall U.S. annual
employment growth rate of 1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reactions to Indonesian President's Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Commenting on Indonesian
President B.J. Habibie's accountability speech on Thursday night,
some politicians described it as pure rhetoric to gloss over the
failings of the administration, the Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his three-hour accountability speech before the plenary
session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), Habibie
devoted a great deal of his speech to elaborating on what his
administration has done to improve the economy, accelerate the
democratization process and carry out reform in other sectors.
</P>
<P>
He spoke at great length, defending his policy on East Timor,
which in late August voted to reject autonomy within Indonesia and
become a separate state.
</P>
<P>
"I hereby urge assembly members to ratify East Timor's
independence vote," Habibie said, pointing out that in various
international forums, Indonesia had always been cornered because
of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Amien Rais, chairman of the National Mandate Party, described
the speech as full of red marks, likening it to a school report.
</P>
<P>
He said credit should be given in areas of freedom of
expression, the release of political prisoners and the birth of a
multiparty system.
</P>
<P>
Amien, who is also chairman of the MPR, however said Habibie
did not fully elaborate on the critical issue of corruption.
</P>
<P>
Habibie in his speech defended a decision of the attorney
general to stop an investigation into alleged corruption by former
President Soeharto, saying, "There isn't enough evidence to prove
irregularities that caused losses to the economy or allowed an
abuse of power by Soeharto."
</P>
<P>
The president pledged to continue investigations into the
businesses of Soeharto's cronies and family members suspected of
collusion and nepotism and to deal with them according to laws.
</P>
<P>
Poll winner the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle chief
Megawati Soekarnoputri hinted that she would likely not approve of
it.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion the speech should be rejected, the reasons will
be presented later by the faction," she added.
</P>
<P>
Matori Abdul Djalil, chairman of the National Awakening Party
(PKB), said his party would likely reject Habibie's
accountability.
</P>
<P>
He said the speech was merely an apology for the wrongdoing or
shortcomings of Habibie's government. "It has yet to reflect the
reality," he added.
</P>
<P>
Declarator of the PKB Abdurrahman Wahid alias Gus Dur said that
he found at least two weaknesses in Habibie's speech and that
Habibie did not touch on the role of mass organizations in coping
with the nation's current problems.
</P>
<P>
Gus Dur, chairman of Indonesia's largest Islamic organization,
Nahdlatul Ulama, said the accountability speech only stressed the
mechanism of resolving the cases of corruption, collusion and
nepotism, but did not socialize the spirit of eliminating the
problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Golkar Party executive Marzuki Darusman said the
president had admitted that his administration failed in solving
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
"In general, we wish to see the accountability accepted," he
added.
</P>
<P>
President of the Justice Party Nur Machmudi Nur Ismail said
there are many positive matters in the speech. The accountability
demonstrated the Habibie administration's bravery to confess past
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
All 11 factions in the MPR are scheduled to present their
responses to the speech on Friday and Saturday. Amien said there
will be a question and answer session before the assembly decides
to accept or reject the speech. If the MPR fails to reach a
consensus on the acceptance, a vote will be the only solution.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that if the speech is accepted it will help
smoothen Habibie's race for presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar Party has nominated Habibie as the party's candidate
for the October 20 presidential election and he is expected to run
against Megawati and Gus Dur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
