<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0369 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Varied Habits of Education Savings: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Given variations uncovered by the survey, there appears to be
no common approach in the Asia-Pacific region as to how much
parents saved for their children's education, said today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
"The differences could be attributed to different government
polices to promoted education, such as different kinds of
scholarships and students loans in those countries," said Feng
Weiquan, senior executive of MasterCard International.
</P>
<P>
Of the 600 people polled in China's major cities of Beijing,
Shanghai and Guangzhou, two-thirds saved for their children's
education with monthly deposits reaching 100-200 yuan (about 12-24
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that pocket money for a child averaged 5
US dollars a week.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 per cent of Chinese parents give their children
allowances, an average of slightly below 50 yuan (6 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 65 per cent of people 17 to 21 years old
have their own bank accounts. Most parents said they believe that
when young people reach the age of 17, they are capable of
handling their own money.
</P>
<P>
Twenty per cent of Chinese Mainland parents thought their
children are capable of handling their pocket money when they
reach 13, the survey reported.
</P>
<P>
From June 1 through June 21 the MasterCard International polled
5,453 people -- all 18 or older and all credit-card holders or
with the financial strength to be approved for credit cards.
</P>
<P>
The poll's respondents were from Australia, the Chinese
mainland, Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, Taiwan, India,
Indonesia, Japan, Republic of Korea, Malaysia, New Zealand, the
Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
