<HEADLINE> Philippines' Trade Surplus Up by 200 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines registered a
trade surplus of 1.305 billion U.S. dollars for the period from
January to August 1999, a 200.9-percent reversal from a deficit of
1.294 billion dollars for the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
A report of the National Statistics Office said Friday that
total merchandise trade for the first eight months of 1999 went up
by 7.6 percent to 42.425 billion dollars from 39.412 billion
dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, payment for imported merchandise
inched up by 1 percent to 20.56 billion dollars from 20.353
billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, receipts from export of goods grew by 14.7
percent to 21.865 billion dollars from 19.059 billion dollars a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For August alone, the total trade amounted to 5.873 billion
dollars, up by 13.8 percent from 5.16 billion dollars last year.
Exports of the month went up by 21.1 percent while imports
increased by 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the high-speed increase in exports, the trade
surplus for August surged by 281.9 percent to 550 million dollars
from 144 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that electronics and components still topped
the import list with a 25.6-percent share in August, followed by
mineral fuels, telecommunication equipment and industrial
machinery.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, purchases of U.S.-made goods led all top imports for
August with a 23.1-percent share while other major sources of
imports for August were Japan, South Korea, Singapore and
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
