<HEADLINE> Canada, U.S. to Further Border Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the United States
will work together to improve border management and generate more
border trade, according to a joint statement released here
Thursday by the Canadian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will streamline border management, increase
customs efficiency as well as collaborate "on common threats from
outside Canada and the United States," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement hailed the world's longest undefended border as "
a model of cooperation and efficiency" and quoted U.S. President
Bill Clinton as saying during his last Friday's trip to Canada
that the progress was "excellent" since 1995, when he paid his
last visit to Ottawa and struck the Shared Border Accord with
Canada.
</P>
<P>
During Clinton's day-long visit, he and Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien confirmed the guiding principles for the border
management, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It noted that Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy and U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright have agreed to establish the
Canada-U.S. Partnership, under which the two countries will hold
regular meetings for promoting border cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The cross-border trade between the two countries was reported
to top 1 billion Canadian dollars (about 678 million U.S. dollars)
last year, with a record of more than 200 million private border
crossings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
