<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong, HK Increasing Cooperation in Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province and Hong Kong will work to cooperate more closely in
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
In a recent joint statement by the Guangdong Provincial People'
s Government and Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
they decided to initiate a special cooperation group for
sustainable development and environmental protection under the
jurisdiction of the existing Guangdong-Hong Kong Joint Cooperation
Conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the new group will be held
responsible for specialized research programs focusing on acid
rain, nitrogen dioxide, pollution from actinic smoke or particles
and measures to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
The group will also fund researches to deal with other subjects
including vehicle exhaust pollution and the possibility to unify
the use of diesel oil in HK and Guangdong, protection of forestry
resources, improvement and protection of water source in Dongjiang
River and at estuary of the Pearl River, impact of urban planning
and development on environment.
</P>
<P>
While encouraging cooperation in environmental researches and
planning, the governments of Guangdong and HKSAR will also strive
to implement plans for improving the environment in Shenzhen and
Dapeng bays and to protect white dolphins, the mascot to mark Hong
Kong's return to the motherland in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0387 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 die, 20,000 Families Displaced in S. Lankan Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- At least two persons died and
20,000 families were rendered homeless in floods resulting from
incessant thundershowers for over a week in Sri Lanka, officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Department of Social Services said the two
were killed in earth slips at Ayagama in the Ratnapura district in
southwestern Sri Lanka and the homeless families were mostly in
the coastal belt of the country.
</P>
<P>
In the Colombo district alone, around 10,000 families have been
displaced, local officials said, adding that the worst-affected
areas are along the western coastal belt, from Wennappuwa to
Puttalam.
</P>
<P>
Displaced families have been given refuge in schools and other
community halls and are provided cooked meals and dry rations. A
sum of 10,000 rupees (140 U.S. dollars) will be paid to each
homeless family.
</P>
<P>
The floods caused by rains have inundated many main roads and
by-roads in many parts of the country and many people were forced
to report to duty late or stay at home, officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Meteorological Department, Thursday's
thunderstorm and gusty winds and accompanying rains were due to
atmospheric disturbances over Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
It added that spells of heavy rain can be expected during the
current active monsoon season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
