<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds World's Earliest Wind Instruments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Scores of exquisite bone
flutes excavated from the Jiahu Relics Site in Central China's
Henan Province have recently been confirmed as the earliest wind
instruments in the world, according to archeologists.
</P>
<P>
The flutes are made of crane bones, and evidence of careful
construction and repeated tuning can be found on them.
</P>
<P>
The flutes, mostly with five to eight holes, sound seven notes,
which means that the ancient Chinese understood the seven-note
musical scale at least 8,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that these flutes are the most complete
musical instruments among all those discovered worldwide which
date back to the same era.
</P>
<P>
The Jiahu Relics Site, located in central Henan, is about 9,000
years old, and the unearthed cultural relics discovered there
represent the grandeur of the upper reaches of the Huaihe River
more than 8,000 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0395 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds World's Earliest Wind Instruments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Scores of exquisite bone
flutes excavated from the Jiahu Relics Site in Central China's
Henan Province have recently been confirmed as the earliest wind
instruments in the world, according to archeologists.
</P>
<P>
The flutes are made of crane bones, and evidence of careful
construction and repeated tuning can be found on them.
</P>
<P>
The flutes, mostly with five to eight holes, sound seven notes,
which means that the ancient Chinese understood the seven-note
musical scale at least 8,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that these flutes are the most complete
musical instruments among all those discovered worldwide which
date back to the same era.
</P>
<P>
The Jiahu Relics Site, located in central Henan, is about 9,000
years old, and the unearthed cultural relics discovered there
represent the grandeur of the upper reaches of the Huaihe River
more than 8,000 years ago. 
</P>
