<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price of Soft Drinks Goes Up by 17% in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The price of soft drinks has
gone up by 17 percent in Zimbabwe this week, owing to the
escalating cost of inputs, the daily Herald reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Soft Drinks Manufacturers' Association Steve
Kuipa was quoted as saying Thursday that price increases are
inevitable if soft drinks manufacturers want to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen two price increases on sugar totalling 42
percent. Water has gone up by 70 percent and electricity has been
going up quarterly, totalling 55 percent since June this year," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in our input costs has seriously eroded the
profitability of the industry and has left us with no option but
to increase the prices of all our brands if we are to remain
viable and continue with our various investment programs into the
industry," he added.
</P>
<P>
Prices of soft drinks were last increased in June this year
following another upward rally in the price of key inputs.
</P>
</TEXT>
