<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Conducts Third Survey on Giant Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A pilot survey on the
distribution of giant pandas, one of the world's most endangered
animal species, began recently in Qingchuan County in southwest
China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
This marks the beginning of the third nationwide survey on the
giant panda which enjoys support from the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
The current survey will be conducted on the basis of two
previous surveys in China, and collates research results on the
species over the past several decades. It will draw opinions from
wildlife experts at home and abroad and is equipped with advanced
devices including the use of satellite location techniques.
</P>
<P>
The scope of the survey includes Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi
provinces over a total area of 13,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
There are only about 1,000 pandas in existence, and they all
live in China's Sichuan, Gansu, and Shaanxi provinces, with 80
percent of them in Sichuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
