<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda to Unite Congo Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda are going to
help the opposing rebel groups of the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD) in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) to
form a joint liberation movement.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both countries who are trying to reconcile
themselves after the clashes in Kisangani in the DRC two months
ago made the promise at a joint press conference in Kigali
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's National Political Commissar James Wapakhabulo, who
led a six- man delegation to Kigali, told reporters after five-day
marathon talks with the Rwandan team that the joint liberation
movement would help the rebels achieve their objective in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Patriotic Front Secretary General Charles Murigande
said that supporting the two rebel factions has been a source of
contention between the two countries and having the two rebel
groups together would reduce the burden on both Uganda and
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The RCD rebels split into two groups in May and Uganda and
Rwanda chose to support the Kisangani faction and Goma faction
respectively. The different stands the two countries have held on
the rebel groups constitute a direct cause to the recent clashes
in Kisangani between the armed forces of Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The clashes claimed more than 200 lives and both sides
sustained heavy material losses. Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame met in time to
prevent escalation of the clashes. The two former allies have
since resolved to mend the souring bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
