<HEADLINE> Zambia Suffers Heavy Losses for Delaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is losing between one to
two million U.S. dollars a month because of the delayed
privatization of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), Finance
and Economic Development Minister Katele Kalumba has said.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambia is on the threshold of economic development
because of its privatization program and a private sector driven
economy, the minister was quoted by Friday's Zambia Daily Mail
newspaper as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The economy has a sound foundation to provide good
opportunities for growth, he said, adding that the government has
over the last three months managed to bring the Structural
Adjustment Program back on course.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will continue to adhere to the cash
budget and strive to run domestic surpluses to eliminate overall
budget deficits, stressing that this would help the government to
save through financial systems and avail the surplus to the
private sector for investment.
</P>
<P>
The government has created a competitive environment for the
financial sector to operate in the country, the minister said,
citing the liberalization of interest rates, the complete removal
of exchange controls and the creation of the new Banking and
Financial Services Act as some of the measures put in place by the
government in this regard. 
</P>
