<HEADLINE> Massive Zimbabwean Dollar Devaluation Erodes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco, which is one of
Zimbabwe's largest foreign currency earners, has lost its glitter
owing to the massive depreciation of the local dollar, sending
fears of foreign currency shortages across the entire economy, the
daily Herald reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decline in earnings from 593.1 million U.S. dollars in 1996
to 334 million U.S. dollars this year has meant that pressure on
the foreign currency market would continue, making it difficult
for the authorities to continue to "manage" the Zimbabwean dollar,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, whose major strength is agriculture, is finding it
difficult to pull through the current economic depression,
particularly in view of the poor tobacco earnings.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Zimbabwean dollar by more than 50
percent since 1997 has chewed up tobacco earnings in U.S. dollar
terms, eroding the envisaged foreign currency inflows that were
supposed to shore up the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Profits that have accrued to farmers during the two-year period
were largely cosmetic because of the currency plunge and the high
inflation rate, which is now at 69.7 percent as of last month,
industry captains have said.
</P>
<P>
There has not been any significant monetary gain to farmers in
real terms, with the situation being made worse by the 10 percent
tobacco levy introduced by the government three years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
