<HEADLINE> Indonesian Capital's Main Street Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Sudirman street, the main
street in the Indonesian capital, was closed Friday following a
clash between students and security personnel on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Masses were still blocking the street through Friday noon. Cars
passing by Sudirman to Blok M area were forced to turn onto other
areas after the masses blocked the thoroughfare with a hijacked
public bus.
</P>
<P>
Another group of masses and students also blocked a road near
the Catholic University of Atmajaya which is not far from the
Semanggi cloverleaf with another hijacked bus.
</P>
<P>
Some shops in the areas along Sudirman street were closed.
Public buses plying the street were not operating on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clash between students and security personnel occurred on
Thursday night when President B.J. Habibie delivered his
accountability speech in the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 23 students, one policeman and one
journalist were injured. Some sustained serious wounds.
</P>
<P>
Many chanted slogans criticizing the president and demanded his
government reopen a corruption investigation against former
president Soeharto that was dropped this week without charging
him.
</P>
<P>
Others urged the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the
country's highest legislative body, to elect general chairman of
the poll winner the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle
(PDI-P) Megawati Soekarnoputri as the next president in the
October 20 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Megawati is expected to race against incumbent president
Habibie and the influential Muslim leader Abdurrahman Wahid, the
founder of the National Awakening Party.
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P finished first in the June election, but it failed to
win a majority in the 700-member MPR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
