<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0415 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planning in Central China Keeps Population Growth Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Henan Province in central
China, the country's most populous province with more than 93
million people, has had some 22 million fewer births over the past
25 years than what would have been the case without the country's
family planning policy.
</P>
<P>
Guo Guangyu, in charge of a survey concerning children below
the age of 16, said that their questionnaires in the province's
five areas show that the money needed to raise a child up to the
age of 16 is 24,000 yuan (about 1,680 U.S. dollars) in the rural
areas and 68,000 yuan in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The 22 million fewer people, therefore, has saved 117.8 billion
yuan, or 3.5 times that of the province's gross domestic product
for last year. This means a great deal to the province's
developing economy, and also contributed to the postponing of the
"World Day of Six Billion People."
</P>
<P>
The family planning policy of the past 25 years has reduced the
province's birthrate from 31.47 per thousand in 1973 to 14.17 per
thousand in 1998, and the population growth rate from 24.2 per
thousand to 7.8 per thousand, with the growth rate steadily
declining during this decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0416 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Adopt New Education System in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's controversial 8-4-4
education system is to be replaced with a new school program by
January 2001, according to a report submitted by the country's
Education Commission of Inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation reported Friday that Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi Thursday asked the Ministry of Education, Science and
Technology to appoint a task force to implement the proposals put
forward by the commission.
</P>
<P>
Details about the report were not available, but the commission
is believed to have called for changes to the 8-4-4 system, which
means eight years of primary school, four years of high school and
four years of university.
</P>
<P>
The current system, introduced 14 years ago, has been widely
criticized by parents and teachers for its heavy workload. It is
too broad, too expensive and too troublesome, they complained.
</P>
</TEXT>
