<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olaru A New Star Shines at Gymnastics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Many predicted that new stars
would overshadow the veterans at the Tianjin gymnastics world
championships, and the shining Romanian fairies proved that was
not rash talk.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Olaru stole the limelight with impeccable
performance in the women's all-around final Thursday, and claimed
her first world glory.
</P>
<P>
"Am I really a world champion? I still can't believe it," said
the newly-crowned champion. Olaru edged pace-setter Vyctoria
Karpenko of Ukraine at the last apparatus to win the coveted title
with 38.774 points.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the history of the world gymnastics
championships that a debutante won the all-around title.
</P>
<P>
No one had listed Olaru a hot favorite for the title, comparing
with such big names as Olympic and world champions Svetlana
Khorkina of Russia and Simona Amanar of Romania.
</P>
<P>
Olaru, all-around silver medalist at last year's Goodwill Games
in New York, had a difficult time when she underwent a knee
operation last October and had to stop training for nearly four
months.
</P>
<P>
"She thought she would never be able to compete again. Once
she had returned to the gym, it became obvious that this incident
happened for a good reason as she was more motivated and she
worked even harder to regain her form," said Maria Bitang, Olaru's
coach.
</P>
<P>
Standing 1.62 meters as the tallest member of the Romanian team,
Olaru planted her name into everyone's heart when she led all the
way through the qualifying round and team final with almost
flawless routines.
</P>
<P>
While Khorkina and Amanar making mistakes in the breathtaking
final, Olaru surged from a temporary seventh place upwards and
finally topped the field after four rotations.
</P>
<P>
"I was more stable than anyone else today. It is as simple as
this," Olaru smiled after the victory. "But it was difficult and
boring when I prepared my routines for hundreds and thousands
times in the gymnasium."
</P>
<P>
"Now I am happy that I have done all these repetitions."
</P>
<P>
Octavian Bellu, head coach for Romania, echoed Olaru's words.
He said: "Maria was the most consistent in this competition, and
this is the explanation to her success."
</P>
<P>
Olaru, who started gymnastics training at the age of six,
wanted to join elite gymnasts like Khorkina, Amanar and Romania's
former world champion Gina Gogean.
</P>
<P>
"The younger are getting stronger and stronger and they have
reached the points where they are able to beat their idols," Bellu
said.
</P>
<P>
"This new generation are hungry for success and with the
Olympic Games approaching, they will be even hungrier to prove
themselves," added Bellu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
