<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0420 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Asset Management Firm Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The China Orient Asset
Management Corporation (COAMC) was officially established here
today, marking another solid step taken by China to handle non-
performing bank loans.
</P>
<P>
China plans to set up four capital asset management firms to
deal with the non-performing loans of its four state-owned
commercial banks. The first of these, China Cinda Asset Management
Corporation, was formed in April this year.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the COAMC said that the new company is an
independent state-owned financial institution under the
supervision of the People's Bank of China, the country's central
bank.
</P>
<P>
With a total registered capital of 10 billion yuan, the COAMC
will mainly focus its business on managing non-performing loans
and assets transferred from the Bank of China, one of the four
state-owned commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The company also has access to trust accounts for other
financial institutions, and is also allowed to sell stock and
creditor rights to overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The 10 billion yuan of capital will be allocated by the
Ministry of Finance, and includes six billion yuan and 500 million
U.S. dollars in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The president and vice-presidents of the COAMC will be
appointed by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the other two asset management corporations
are likely be established early next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
