<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Move to Improve Sewage Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua)-- Three central government
departments issued a circular Thursday on strengthening the
collection of sewage treatment fees besides the regular charges
for water, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The circular, released by the State Development Planning
Commission, Ministry of Construction and State Environmental
Protection Administration, also urged local governments to build a
drainage and centralized sewage treatment system in cities.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qifeng, an official with the State Environmental
Protection Administration, said that the circular has guaranteed
funds for operating sewage treatment equipment, and will
contribute to environmental protection in China.
</P>
<P>
Only a few Chinese cities charge users the sewage treatment
fees, and the charges are often too low to make up for the cost of
operating and maintaining sewage treatment equipment.
</P>
<P>
Some users occasionally evade payment and embezzle public funds.
Some sewage treatment factories cannot even afford to operate the
equipment because of insufficient funds, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
In order to solve the problem, the circular stipulates that
sewage treatment fees should be collected along with water fees
from users in all cities depending on the water used. In Beijing,
water consumers pay 0.3 yuan for each ton of water used.
</P>
<P>
The collected revenue will go towards sewage treatment
enterprises, which assume sole responsibility for their profits or
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
