<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Friday,
as investors remained reluctant to buy stocks on worries over the
uncertainty in New York stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 178.69 points, or 1.00
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 17,601.57.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 26.48 points or 1.72 percent to 1,
510.26.
</P>
<P>
Concerns grew that Wall Street may turn downward Friday
following a report that U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan urged U.S. bankers Thursday to prepare for a sudden
plunge in domestic share prices, making investors in Tokyo
reluctant to buy shares, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 769.47 million
shares from 841.43 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were lower in 22 of the 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Banks, the biggest winners Thursday following reports of a
merger between Sakura Bank and Sumitomo Bank, fell back on profit-
taking,losing 2.65 percent as a group.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented technology issues were also weak, hit by the
yen's upturn against the U.S. dollar, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 746 to 453, with 137 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
