<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEM Science Ministers Meeting Concludes in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Science and technology
ministers from 25 members of the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) ended
their two-day meeting here today after adopting a ministerial
communique and the chairman's statement.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation should be conducted on an equal and voluntary
basis, with equal opportunities rendered to all ASEM members to
join in regional S &AMP; T (science and technology) programs," the
ministers' communique said.
</P>
<P>
The communique notes that cooperation should aim at common
development, with due consideration to the different interests of
participating countries.
</P>
<P>
"Policy dialogue on S &AMP; T cooperation should be conducted in a
timely manner among S &AMP; T policy makers and leading officials of
the two continents," the document says.
</P>
<P>
The ASEM ministers and officials from the Commission of the
European Union identify a number of areas for potential
cooperation where they have common interests and priorities.
</P>
<P>
These include basic science, use of large-scale scientific
facilities, knowledge transfer from research institutes and
universities to industry, human resources development, and
agricultural S &AMP; T such as forestry and water management.
</P>
<P>
Also on the priority list are environmental protection issues,
including sustainable development of cities, clean production
technologies, sustainable development of ecosystems and cultural
heritage, as well as upgrading the technical and research
capabilities of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after today's closing ceremony, Zhu Lilan,
Chinese science and technology minister, said the meeting will
leave its mark on the history of Asia-Europe cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
