<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Has Great Potential for Economic Development: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region in northwest China, with its abundance of coal, petroleum,
and mineral resources, will very possibly become the focus of
China's development in the next century, said Dr. T.C. Tso, board
chairman of the Institute of International Development and
Education in Agriculture and Life Science (IDEALS).
</P>
<P>
Dr. Tso said at the ongoing International Symposium and
Exhibition on Fruit and Vegetable Processing Technology and
Industrialization in Shandong Province, that Xinjiang, if it can
solve the problem of water shortage, will very likely develop into
one of the country's main agricultural and industrial areas.
</P>
<P>
He made a comparison with California in the U.S., which has
similar conditions, saying that the west coast American state has
been able to grow into a developed area by channeling water from
the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
With his knowledge of southwestern China, including the Tibet
Autonomous Region, from his several visits, he thinks it possible
that China can channel water from the southwest, including
Tongtian and Jinsha rivers at the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River, the Lancang River, the Nujiang River and the Yalung Zangbo
River, into the Yellow River to solve water shortage problem in
the northwest.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country should also make good use of the
resources, especially water resources, in the west for its own
development, rather than totally rely on the east.
</P>
<P>
"When western China is able to depend on itself for further
economic growth, it will bring a bright future to the country's
agriculture and economy," said Dr. Tso with confidence.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, with about one-sixth of the country's total area, is
the largest province in China, while its population is only around
17 million, or some one percent of the country's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
