<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tea Remains Favorite Drink for Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Tea remains the favorite drink
for Chinese people, despite a sharp increase in the consumption of
other beverages such as sodas, juice and mineral water over the
past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Participants attending a recent seminar here predicted that by
the middle of the next century, the annual per-capita consumption
of tea is expected to top one kilo, compared with the present 0.6
kg.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 tea experts from across the country attended the
seminar held in Guiyang, the provincial capital of Guizhou, in
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
China is the original home of tea and one of the largest tea
producers in the world, with the country's tea plantation acreage
standing at 760,000 hectares, the largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
During the 1993-95 period, China's tea industry was badly hurt
by the rapid expansion of other drinks, and saw its output plummet
by 50 percent to 400,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, however, tea has regained its reputation among
Chinese because of its healthy and nutritious qualities.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China saw a notable recovery in tea production,
which topped 665,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0450 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Newcomers Call the Shots in World Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- It is a trend the veterans can
not beat that more and more newcomers are emerging out of their
shadow.
</P>
<P>
And the trend was underlined in the world gymnastics
championships here which saw favored veterans fell off one after
another and fresh faces came to the stage and put the color medals
to their credit.
</P>
<P>
Simona Amanar and Svetlana Khorkina were still impressive and
Alexei Nemov and Ivan Ivankov remained aggressive. But they had
been strongly feeling the pressure exerted by those who have honed
their techniques under their shadow.
</P>
<P>
Maria Olaru, 17, became the new queen of gymnastics as she beat
a strong field to finish 38.774 points to win the women's
individual all-round competition on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian is not alone as Vyctoria Karpenko of Ukraine, 18,
and Elena Zamolodchikova of Russia, 17, both outshone the more
experienced gymnasts to grab a place on the awarding podium.
</P>
<P>
It is a up-or-down matter as Amanar had to settle for a 14th
place and Khorkina only ended up 12th as their errors like falling
and shaking on the apparatuses cost them a lot.
</P>
<P>
Romania's legendary coach Octavian Bellu, who has guided his
women's "Dream Teams" to four straight world championships team
titles, exuded his joy to the emergence and maturity of the young
gymnasts while expressing respect to the old.
</P>
<P>
"This event also proved that a new wave gymnasts are coming
into the spotlight...the younger gymnasts were getting stronger
and stronger and they have reached the point where they are able
to beat their idols."
</P>
<P>
"This new generation are hungry for success and with the
Olympic Games approaching , they will be even hungrier to prove
themselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I respect very much Khorkina and our Simona Amanar. Svetlana
started the competition with a hiccup on the beam and Simona
burned her out on her last piece, the Uneven Bars. But both have
contributed so much for their team -- fighting for so many years
and resisting constant pressure to win titles and events one after
another."
</P>
<P>
"Simona is now 20 years old and it is extremely hard to keep up
with the development of gymnastics at that age. Still she managed
to do this and she is a huge credit and support to our team."
</P>
<P>
The change in leadership also happened to the men's side as
world champion Ivankov and 1996 Atlanta champion Nemov are all
struggling with the an injury which kept them hot in preview but
cold in competition.
</P>
<P>
Ivankov, who has been poised to make history to become the
first three-time world champions in all-round competition with a
gold here, was forced to withdraw from the competition after
finished a 7.975 points in the horizontal bar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Injury had forced him to miss the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and
stopped him from making his mark again in the world championships.
</P>
<P>
Nemov also failed to became less aggressive as injury had kept
him from normal training and his routines' start value had dropped
before he finally came in sixth only at the competition.
</P>
<P>
While their shine dimmed the unknown young gymnasts flexed
their muscle and begun to call the shots.
</P>
<P>
Nikolay Krukov of Russia, Naoya Tsukahara of Japan and Jordan
Jovtchev of Bulgaria were the final three who smilingly waved the
flowers on the podium as the veterans lipped their wound nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
