<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49 Injured in Clash in Indonesian Capital: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 49 persons were
injured in a clash between students and security personnel in
Indonesian capital Thursday night, Police spokesman Brig. Gen.
Togar Sianipar told reporters here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 49 injured, 11 were security personnel, four civilians
and 34 were demonstrators," he said, adding that at least eight
persons were arrested following the clash.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of protesters returned to the streets as the second
round of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) general session
kicked off on Thursday night with the accountability speech of
President B.J. Habibie as its main agenda.
</P>
<P>
Many chanted slogans criticizing the president and demanded his
government reopen a corruption investigation against former
president Soeharto that was dropped this week without charging
him.
</P>
<P>
Masses were still blocking Sudirman street, Jakarta's main
street, through Friday noon.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the road blockade, traffic flow in Sudirman area
has virtually stopped and the traffic itself is in disorder.
</P>
<P>
At least three automobiles were heavily damaged or burned by
the masses.
</P>
<P>
Sianipar expressed the hope that until the end of the MPR
general session on October 21, the situation both in the capital
city and the regions will remain calm and called on the people to
trust the police and the security personnel in pacifying the
session.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the people to be wiser and not to be easily
provoked.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the spate of demonstrations, Chairman of the MPR
Amien Rais Friday expressed concern that Indonesia might turn into
a cold-blooded nation if bloody demonstrations become habitual.
</P>
<P>
"They (the bloody demonstrations) should be avoided," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest legislative body, will elect new
president on October 20 and new vice president on October 21.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent President Habibie, which was nominated by the Golkar
Party, is expected to race against General Chairman of the poll
winner the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P)
Megawati Soekarnoputri and the influential Muslim leader
Abdurrahman Wahid in the presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
