<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0457 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 86th China Export Commodity Fair Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) --The 86th China (Autumn) Export
Commodity Fair opened today in Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong Province, with the attendance of over 2,000
businesspeople from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The fair is a biannual event that is popularly considered a
weathervane for China's foreign trade. There are 6,900 booths at
the fair, which will spotlight IT commodities, home appliances,
and high-tech and famous brands products.
</P>
<P>
On-line service for the export fair, the second of the kind,
will also be available, and a great number of seminars and
symposiums will be held during the fair, which is expected to
attract many multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
Due to the negative impact of Asian financial crisis and the
fluctuating international market, China has met with setbacks in
foreign trade since 1997. But the country's foreign trade began to
pick up in July.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that by September, China exported 137
billion U.S. dollars worth of commodities, up 2.1 percent from
the same period last year and the first positive rise in the
country's export since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The fair, sponsored by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation, will last for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the 13th China Overseas-Financed
Ventures Export Commodity Fair, sponsored by the China Overseas-
Financed Ventures Association, also opened today in Guangzhou.
This fair will display commodities made of grass, willow, bamboo
and rattan.
</P>
<P>
The previous 12 fairs attracted 43,000 businesspeople from
around the world, and saw the signing of export contracts worth 1.
8 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
