<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese-Sponsored Dyke Reinforcement Project Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINGJIANG (HUBEI Province), October 15 (Xinhua) -- An
embankment project on the Jingjiang dyke in central China's Hubei
Province, which utilizes steel pile anti-seepage technology for
the first in China, started today.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, 2.2 kilometers of anti-seepage wall will be
built in the Guanyinsi section of the Jingjiang dyke and the Yanwo
section of the Honghu dyke.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government provided nearly 1.5 billion Japanese
yen (about 117 million U.S. dollars) in aid for the project and
the Chinese side added some 40 million yuan (about 5.4 million
dollars) to get the project started.
</P>
<P>
The structure will enhance the anti-seepage quality of the two
sections, which are regarded as very important for preventing
floods along the Yangtze River, said a Chinese water resource
expert, adding that some 7.5 million local people will benefit
from the project.
</P>
<P>
It has been learned that Japan provided six billion Japanese
yen of free aid to China last year. From 1981 to 1998, Japan
provided a total of 107.7 billion Japanese yen in free aid to
China, and this money has been mainly used for China's agriculture,
education medical facilities and environmental protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
