<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Its Largest Oil Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A contract for the building of
China's largest oil ship was signed today in Dalian, a sea port in
northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the Dalian New Shipyard under the
China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation, one of the largest
shipbuilders in China, will be responsible for building the
floating production and storage off-loading (FPSO) weighing 150,
000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The FPSO, a special unit for off-shore oil production, will be
put into use in the Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oil Field in July 2001.
</P>
<P>
It is by far the largest FPSO designed and built in China, said
Sha Jungang, director of the shipyard, which beat world-famous
builders including Samsung, Mitsubishi and Kawasaki to win the
bidding for the contract.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the FPSO is co-funded by the China National
Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC) and two U.S. oil companies,
Texaco and Arco, with CNOOC as the major shareholder.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
