<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NGO Conference Adopts Seoul Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The 1999 international conference
of the Non-Governmental Organizations (NGO) ended here Friday
afternoon with the adoption of the Seoul Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The Seoul Declaration, entitled "Fulfillment of A Vision for the
21st Century," highlighted the need to strengthen friendly and
cooperative ties among its member states by sharing resources,
experience and abilities.
</P>
<P>
All NGO states will strive to maintain transparency and
independence in their operation, build constructive relations with
governments and act to enhance human rights and mutual trust, the
NGO said in the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The five-day Seoul conference, with the participation of some
800 deputies of 1,115 non-governmental bodies from over 100
countries, has discussed issues on human rights, sustainable
development, the well-being of children, gender quality, peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which was designed to reflect common values,
ideals and goals on the eve of the new millennium, said the
upcoming 21st century will be an NGO era to be marked by
widespread civic involvement in all phases of work on behalf of
the human family and United Nations endeavors.
</P>
<P>
Participants said the conference has provided an opportunity to
establish a new paradigm of civil society for the next century and
the Seoul Declaration will envision the future of NGO movement in
the coming millennium.
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly hosted by the NGO Conference in
Consultative Relationship with the United Nations, Executive
Committee of the NGO associated with the Office of Public
Information of the United Nations and Kyunghee University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0472 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Taxes on Special Savings Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China will not levy taxes on
savings accounts used exclusively for educational purposes or
other special savings accounts and funds as designated by taxation
authorities.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the State Administration of Taxation (SAT) said
that this applies to housing subsidies, medical insurance, basic
life insurance, and unemployment insurance funds.
</P>
<P>
China will begin to levy taxes on the interest of regular
savings accounts at a rate of 20 percent on November 1.
</P>
<P>
The tax will be levied on the interest of all yuan and foreign
currency savings accounts that an individual has opened in any
bank in China, with an exemption for interest generated before
November 1.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the tax payment in a month should be
turned over to the central state coffers within seven days of the
next month, and tax on foreign currency savings account should be
levied in their respective currency, but they should be changed
into yuan, the Chinese currency, when they are turned over to the
state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
