<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0473 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos, U.S. Sign Anti-Narcotics Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Laos and the United States have
signed an agreement under which the U.S. government will
contribute 3.338 million U.S. dollars to the Lao government for
counter-narcotics activities, Lao official news agency KPL
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chairman of the Lao National
Commission for Drug Control and Supervision (LCDC) Soubanh
Sritthirath and U.S. Charge d'Affaires to Laos Karen Stewart.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to stop mountainous area opium poppy
cultivation by helping farmers find other sources of income.
</P>
<P>
This U.S. funding will be used to complete construction of the
Sone Tay-Meuang Peu road, and to develop commercial silk
production and other activities.
</P>
<P>
Of the funding, 2.288 million dollars will be used in a
Lao-American Crop Control and Development Project in the districts
of Samphanh and Boun Tay in Phongsaly province. This will support
the Lao government policy of ending opium cultivation by building
rural infrastructure and supporting the development of alternative
sources of income and food security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 600,000 dollars will be used in the Lao-American
Crop Control and Development Project in the districts of
Viengthong and Houameuang of Houaphanh province.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 450,000 dollars are for continued support to the
counter-narcotics law enforcement units in Vientiane and the
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The LCDC and the U.S. Embassy in Vientiane recently signed an
amendment to the existing bilateral agreements between the two
countries on counter-narcotics cooperation. The amendment provides
72,500 dollars from the U.S. government to the Lao-U.S.
Cooperation Project in Houaphanh province.
</P>
<P>
KPL quoted a statement of the U.S. Embassy in Vientiane as
saying that the U.S. government is pleased to continue cooperation
with the Lao government to eliminate opium production and reduce
drug addiction and trafficking in Laos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
