<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Food Agency Aids Drought Affected Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Fti, according to a
news release available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
WFP's initial emergency program will provide 414 tons of food,
including rice, sugar and blended foods, to nearly 30,000
hunger-stricken people,.
</P>
<P>
The current drought in the African country is causing serious
food insecurity in five districts, said WFP Djibouti country
director Sanda Maina.
</P>
<P>
Women, children and the elderly are extremely vulnerable, he
said, adding that "many school children are eating only one meal a
day consisting of boiled rice with a little sugar or salt."
</P>
<P>
According to a joint drought assessment mission of WFP and
Djibouti, 80,000 to 100,000 people will be in urgent need for food
assistance in the coming six months if the current climatic
conditions do not improve.
</P>
<P>
WFP is the United Nations' front-line agency in fighting
against global hunger. Last year, a total of 75 million people,
most of the world's refugees included, were fed by the agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
