<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Quits Transparency International Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's President Olusegun
Obasanjo, has resigned his post as the chairman of the Advisory
Council of Transparency International (TI), a Berlin-based
international anti-corruption coalition he co-founded.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 yearly report of the organization released at the
on-going 9th International Anti-corruption Conference held in
Durban, South Africa, said the position was bestowed on Obasanjo
when he was imprisoned by the government of late Gen. Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
"Upon my election as President of Nigeria, I have had to resign
the chairmanship of the Transparency International (TI) advisory
council," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo added that his involvement with TI was indeed a great
and wonderful opportunity to assist in fashioning an enduring
framework for tackling with vigor the often time corrosive,
deleterious and debilitating scourge that corruption has become.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that I have a well spring of ideas to draw on as we
also attempt to confront headlong the erection of an integrity
system in Nigeria ... and in seeking to leave an enduring legacy
of zero to corruption."
</P>
<P>
Kamal Hossain from Bangladesh has succeeded Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The organization listed Nigeria earlier this year as the top
corruptive country in the world, which was generally considered as
a result of decades of mismanagement by former military regimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
