<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Veteran Politician Josef Burg Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Josef Burg, founder of
Israel's National Religious Party (NRP), died Friday at the age of
90.
</P>
<P>
Born in Dresden, Germany, Burg arrived in British-mandated
Palestine just before the outbreak of World War II in 1939. He
spent 40 years in the Knesset (parliament) after Israel's
establishment in 1948 and served as health, posts, welfare,
interior, police and religious portfolios in the government until
his retirement from politics in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Burg symbolized the elite of European Jews who long dominated
politics in Israel. His NRP spearheaded Jewish settlement efforts
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, areas Israel occupied in the 1967
Middle East War. However, Burg was widely regarded as a dove among
ranks in the party.
</P>
<P>
After Israel's signing of the peace treaty with Egypt in 1979,
Burg led a Palestinian Autonomy Committee that failed to make
progress on Palestinian self-rule, later realized under an
interim peace deal signed between Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"Israel has lost one of its senior public servants, a man who
led the religious Zionist camp for dozens of years and worked
tirelessly on behalf of all the people," Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said in a condolence statement.
</P>
<P>
Burg's son, Avraham Burg, is currently speaker of the 15th
Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0484 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
