<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed 1.3 percent lower Friday as local bond yields soared and
investors fear that interest rate hikes are imminent.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index fell 39 points to close at
2,862.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Comments by U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan
indicating a potential bubble in equity prices added to concerns
that interest rates will rise. That fear was mirrored locally with
the yield on the benchmark 10-year bond closing at 6.69 percent,
its highest level since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials fell 66.9 points to 4,914.9 and the all
resources index 17.4 points weaker at 1,270.9.
</P>
<P>
Among the interest rate sensitive bank stocks the National
Australia Bank slid 41.8 cents to 15 U.S. dollars, the
Commonwealth was steady at 15.99 U.S. dollars, Westpac fell 9.7
cents to 6.05 U.S. dollars while the ANZ bank shaved off 18.7
cents to 6.46 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most leading resource stocks also lost ground with Rio Tinto
leading the slump sliding 0.65 U.S. dollars to 16.67 U.S. dollars,
while BHP managed to end in positive territory by adding one cent
to 11.66 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 504.93 million shares worth 708 million
U.S. dollars. There were 755 falling stocks, 514 rising stocks and
416 stocks were steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
