<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Share prices nose-dived on
Singapore Stock Market Friday amid fears of a drop on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) dropped 51.29 points to
end at 2,061.25 points in light dealings. The decline was the
biggest fall since August 5, 1999, that saw a drop of 61.87
points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 203.65 million units valued at 442.56
million Singapore dollars (264.07 million U.S. dollars) with
losers outstripping gainers by 297 to 31, a ratio about 10 to one,
and 124 counters remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
HMI topped the volume list registering a turnover of 39.54
million units. It was followed by CMTel which had 17.43 million
shares done. Gen Int was the next with 9.66 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Boustd w04 and MulIMBML pw99 was the top active stocks of the
day edging up six cents to end at 0.56 and 0.14 Singapore dollars
respectively. ASJ Hldgs, DelGro 500, KepHZ and SingInv inched up
five cents each to finish at 0.90, 5.20, 1.05 and 1.40 Singapore
dollars separately.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH was the biggest loser of the day, plunging
by 190 cents to close at 29.80 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 dropped
170 cents to finish at 30.00 Singapore dollars. Shang Asia sank
140 cents to end at 8.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was weakened by fears of a drop on Wall
Street following a warning by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan of the possibility of a fall in U.S. stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
