<HEADLINE> HK District Council Nominees Urged to Sign up Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the
Registration and Electoral Office of Hong Kong reminded nominees
intending to run in the District Councils election to hand in
their nomination forms as early as practicable before the
nomination period closes next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We would advise nominees not to hand in forms in the last
minute. They should allow leeway to rectify mistakes in the
entries on their forms and not to put themselves in the risk of
having their nomination being invalidated," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 640 people have already submitted nomination forms
in the past eight days since the two-week nomination period
started on October 7.
</P>
<P>
A total of 390 District Council members will be elected on
Sunday, November 28 to join 18 District Councils.
</P>
<P>
"Any registered elector aged 21 or above and has ordinarily
lived in Hong Kong for the three years immediately before the
nomination may join the race," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Nominees must hand in their completed nomination forms in
person to the Returning Officer of the constituency they are
contesting and pay a deposit in the sum of 3,000 HK dollars (about
384 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Each nomination must be subscribed by at least 10 registered
electors in the constituency the nominee is contesting. Each
elector is entitled to subscribe to only one nomination.
</P>
<P>
"Nominees should play safe and solicit the support of more than
10 subscribers in case some of the subscribers may be found
ineligible after validation by Returning Officers," the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
