<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni Ministry of Agriculture and Water Resources
has launched a national project to enhance the production of
cotton in cooperation with the private sector and cooperative
societies in the cotton-growing provinces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a committee was set up to examine ways and means for
promoting the production and exports of cotton. The committee
comprises representatives of the Central Bank, the Agricultural
Cooperative Credit Bank, the Yemeni Bank for Reconstruction and
Development and the Agricultural and Fisheries Promotion Fund.
</P>
<P>
Yemen saw its cotton production increase from 13.8 million
pounds (6,230 tons) to 27.6 million pounds (12,500 tons) during
the 1997/98 season and it is expected to reach 76 million pounds
(34,500 tons) by the end of the current season, director of
Agricultural Services Abdullah Baashar said.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Al Zamil Air Conditioners Company has
signed a contract with a offshoot of Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries Company worth some 5.3 million U.S. dollars to provide
high intensity air conditioning sets to the Ghazlan project, a
2,400-megawatt electric plant.
</P>
<P>
Al Zamil Air Conditioners will be importing cooling systems
from Mitsubishi starting November until May 2000.
</P>
<P>
Al Zamil, producing 440,000 window air conditioners a year,
exports its products to more than 23 countries in Europe, America,
Africa and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan produced 407.7 million cigarettes during the
first seven months of 1999, down by 48.97 percent from 798.9
million cigarettes during the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the production last July has increased by 43.6 percent
with an output of 80.1 million cigarettes as compared to 59.5
million cigarettes last June, the Al Charq Al Awsat newspaper
quoted a Central Bank statistical bulletin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin showed that Jordan's cigarette production during
1998 amounted to more than 1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Egyptian company has been founded to supervise the
operation and maintenance of the electricity stations established
by the Egyptian and foreign private sector according to the
build-operate-transfer system.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Company for Engineering Consultations and
Electricity Station would contribute 50 percent of the would-be
company and the Commercial International Bank about 25 percent,
said Minister of Electricity and Energy Ali Fahmi el-Saeedi. A
foreign partner will provide the remaining 25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0508 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Freezes Former Nigerian Leader's Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland has frozen the bank
accounts held by former Nigerian leader Sani Abacha, his family
members and some associates at the request of the Nigerian
government.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Friday quoted a statement by Swiss
Federal Office for Police Matters as saying that the accounts were
frozen on Wednesday at five banks: four in Geneva and one in
Zurich.
</P>
<P>
Besides the late Head of State Abacha, the accounts also
belonged to his widow Maryam, his eldest surviving son Mohammed
and his brother Abdul Kabir, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Others who came under the hammer are Abacha's National Security
Adviser Alhaji Ismaila Gwarzo, former minister Abubakar Attiku
Bagudu, four Nigerian business executives and a series of
companies.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland made the decision when Mohammed Abacha, the late
Head of State' s eldest surviving son, Personal Security Chief
Hamza Al-Mustapha and four other former security operatives were
charged Thursday with the murder of Kudirat Abiola, wife of the
late millionaire and opposition politician Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss statement neither named the banks where the accounts
were frozen, nor indicated the amounts involved, saying the
federal police authorities in Bern had not yet been informed of
the value of the frozen assets.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the freezing of the accounts is
provisional, based on a preliminary request from a Geneva attorney
representing the Olusegun Obasanjo administration.
</P>
<P>
"Nigerian authorities suspect that for some years Sani Abacha
and the others 'systematically plundered' the Nigerian Central
Bank," the statement said, adding that Abacha and his group will
be charged with crimes including "embezzlement, fraud, forgery and
money laundering."
</P>
<P>
The Swiss authorities cited Nigeria's Justice Minister Kanu
Agabi as having consolidated the various criminal proceedings
against members of the alleged criminal organization founded by
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has three months to file a formal request for mutual
legal assistance indicating the relationship between criminal
proceedings in the country and the assets frozen in Switzerland,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who took office on May 29, promised at his inaugural
ceremony to foster a "new moral direction" for the country, which
had been devastated by years of poor military rule.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, who seized power in 1993 after the turmoil that
followed a presidential election annulled by the military, ruled
the oil-producing country with an iron fist. He died in June,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Some newspapers suggested that corruptive officials under
different military regimes had looted over 30 billion U.S. dollar
state assets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
