<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0519 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Turns to Kodak to Help Preserve Rare Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese documentary authorities
and Kodak's branch in China jointly held a seminar here this week
to explore ways of using microfilm to preserve the country's
hundreds of millions of state documents.
</P>
<P>
Kodak company displayed its Kodak InfoGuard System at the
seminar in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Yiquan, an official from the State Archives
Bureau, confidentiality and security issues have become major
concerns of computer science. The present electronic document has
major shortcomings yet to be overcome, he said, namely the
relatively short life span of the carrier of information, the
rapid evolution of technological standards of both software and
hardware, and the difficulties in proving the authenticity of
electronic documents.
</P>
<P>
He said that microfilm technologies should be developed quickly
in order to provide a strong and reliable backup for the
electronic archives.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 240 million files of documents in
government-run archives around the country. About ten percent of
them must be preserved permanently. Many are yet to be made public
and concern major historical events that have occurred since the
New China was founded 50 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
