<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0522 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperatives Guarding Against Financial Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese cooperatives at various
levels have begun a massive investigation into the use of large
sums paid in shares by farmers and employees in a bid to
circumvent possible financial fraud.
</P>
<P>
Raising funds among farmers is an important way to enhance the
supply of local goods and boost marketing in order to provide
better services for farmers. But in recent years, some of the
money raised for farmers has been illegally channeled for other
uses, such as providing banking services.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ruzhen, deputy director of the All China Federation of
Supply and Marketing Cooperatives, said that "without the fund,
cooperatives cannot play their proper role in serving farmers. The
urgent task is to return the farmers' money for their needs."
</P>
<P>
Fund misuse is mainly concentrated in several provinces, and
many of them are dealing with the problem, said Bi Meijia, who is
also with the federation.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, local cooperatives had raised 27.7 billion
yuan, among which 14.5 billion yuan belonged to farmers, 6.4
billion yuan to cooperative employees, and 5.9 billion yuan to
urban residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
