<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEF to Hold East Asia Economic Summit in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Switzerland-based World
Economic Forum (WEF), in partnership with the Singapore Economic
Development Board, will hold its 8th East Asia Economic Summit in
Singapore on October 18-20.
</P>
<P>
WEF Managing Director Claude Smadja told a press conference
here Friday that some 900 high-level business representatives from
WEF member companies, heads of government and key ministers from
the region as well as leaders from international organizations
will take part in the forum.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad will deliver key-note
speeches at plenary sessions and Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong will give a key-note address at an official opening dinner
where Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew will also exchange
views with the delegates.
</P>
<P>
Smadja said the summit is designed to give a strong message
that Asia is back on growth and to emphasize the long process and
enormous task East Asia is facing in ensuring economic recovery,
long-term growth and stability.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the summit will feature a series of briefings
on highly relevant and specialized subjects for in-depth analysis
and experience sharing as well as for in-depth updates on national
economies with government leaders and senior officials from each
country and economy.
</P>
<P>
The topics on the agenda include the way forward after emerging
from the Asian financial crisis, economic outlook for Asia, the
road to a sustainable recovery in Asia, the management of
sovereign and corporate risk, banking and financial restructuring,
corporate structuring, major uncertainty factors in the region,
the building of competitiveness in knowledge-based economy,
electronic-commerce in Asia, and monetary stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
WEF held its 7th East Asia Economic Summit also in Singapore in
October 1998 when regional economies were struggling to overcome
the financial crisis that swept Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
