<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0525 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asian Business Advantage Leading to New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- In moving into the new
millennium, Asian business will have a competitive advantage as it
has experienced dramatic shifts in economic environments in a
relatively short period, business leaders here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Participants at a closed forum, entitled "Managing the Speed of
Change: Meeting the Needs of Tomorrow", believed that the business
community will drive much of the speed of change in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders said that Asia's ability to begin recovery is
a strong indicator of the resilience and agility of a majority of
Asian business to changes in the market environment.
</P>
<P>
Leadership, corporate flexibility and transformation, e-
commerce, brand building, applying technology, and developing a
21st century workforce will all determine just how successful that
change will be, they said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening dinner of the Business Week CEO Forum
held at the Grand Hyatt Hotel Wednesday evening, Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
said that Hong Kong's economic philosophy has remained unchanged
since it became a special administrative region of China on July 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been successful for a long time because of its
belief in the free market, its belief in letting market forces
dictate the pace of the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to believe this very strongly," Tung noted. "We do
not wish to interfere at all. We will only interfere when the
market is being distorted, or being monopolized." He also spoke of
his vision and plan to position Hong Kong as Asia's premier
international city in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Because Asia's future is inevitably linked to China's future,
the participation of senior Chinese government officials at the
forum was met with great enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
Yu Xiaosong, chairman of China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade (CCPIT), said, "As Asia copes with the
aftermath of the region's financial crisis, China will no doubt
serve as a driver of much of Asia's recovery."
</P>
<P>
Yu said that globalization has shown a growing momentum and
China as the largest developing nation in the world is seizing the
opportunities and embracing the challenges with a more open
mentality and greater enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
The CCPIT vows to make greater contribution to the promotion of
Sino-foreign economic and trade cooperation as well as China's
integration with the rest of the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. president George Bush's address on "moving into the
new millennium" at the closing ceremony became the climax of the
three-day Third Annual Business Week CEO Forum, which was
sponsored by the Better Hong Kong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Bush expressed his confidence in the sustainment of Asia's
economic recovery and China's entry to WTO.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 global business and political leaders joined in the
discussions on strategies and leadership Asia will require to
sustain the region's return to economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0526 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea, Venezuela Seeking Closer Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Venezuela Friday
agreed to strengthen economic ties between them by promoting
cooperation in construction and telecommunication.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached here Friday afternoon by South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and his Venezuelan counterpart Hugo Chavez,
who arrived here for a three-day visit Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed ways to enhance bilateral relations
and agreed to push forward the South Korean-Venezuelan cooperation
in road construction, telecommunication and petroleum industries,
said South Korean presidential spokesman Park Joon-young after the
summit.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that South Korea's capital and technology can be
combined with Venezuela's natural resources and workforce to
maximize potential for bilateral economic cooperation," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
South Korean officials said the summit will provide momentum
toward fostering trade and investment ties between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
South Korean businessmen are now getting involved in various
business projects ranging from oil drilling and refining and road
construction to mobile communications and defense industry.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade volume between the two countries stood at 2.95
million U.S. dollars last year. South Korean exports, which mostly
were electronics, steel, footwear, automobile and textile,
amounted to 2.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chave's visit is the first one by a Venezuelan president since
the two states established diplomatic relations in 1965.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the third leg of Chave's Asian-European tour,
which has taken him to China and Japan. He will visit Malaysia,
Singapore, the Philippines, Spain and France later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
