<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l PC Giant Wants Bigger Share in Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett Packard (HP),
announcing a formal march into China's personal computer market
here today, unveiled its plan to become one of the three largest
home PC sellers in the country in the coming three years.
</P>
<P>
HP is the last of the world's four largest computer giants to
sell PCs in China, following Compaq, IBM and Dell.
</P>
<P>
China, whose 1.2 billion population has long been a target for
international computer manufacturers, is poised to become the
second-largest PC market by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
China's home PC sales account for 34 percent of Asia-Pacific's
total and has swelled by 50-80 percent a year, according to latest
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 40 percent of families living in developed countries
have purchased a home computer, while in China, only four percent
of 46 million urban Chinese families own a computer.
</P>
<P>
Eager to share the booming home PC market in China, where local
computer makers have been busy marketing their low-price products,
HP has introduced its new PCs with some unique features, including
a CD writer and a one-touch keyboard.
</P>
<P>
HP hopes its high quality and easy-to-use products, along with
its sales warranties could be helpful as it explores the Chinese
market.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, HP began to sell its home PCs in North America, and to
date it ranks second there and first in Asia-Pacific Region for
those computers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
