<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul, Washington to Resume Talks on U.S. Stationing Troops' Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Seoul and Washington have agreed
to resume talks on revising the Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA)
before the end of the year, said South Korean Foreign Ministry
Hong Soon-young Friday.
</P>
<P>
The SOFA is designed to regulate the legal status of United
States troops on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached last Wednesday when U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State Stanley Roth came here to help form a
coordination group on the Nogunri incident -- an ocurrence in
which South Korean civilians were killed by U.S. troops in 1950
early on in the Korean War -- and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean minister said the talks will attempt to settle
priority issues first and then move on to other problems.
</P>
<P>
Among the priority issues is the handover of U.S. servicemen
accused of murder and rape during the Nogunri incident to South
Korean authorities.
</P>
<P>
Under the current SOFA, accused U.S. serviceman will be handed
over to South Korea only after a court sentence is given.
</P>
<P>
Both Seoul and Washington have agreed in principle to transfer
the accused to South Korea but they remain divided over whether to
allow legal counsel to attend interrogations of suspects.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean legal system allows the prosecution to appeal
to a higher court against any lower court ruling that prosecutors
believe unsatisfactory, while the U.S. one does not allow the
prosecution to appeal to a higher court case that a lower court
has found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
Other issues such as Environmental pollution and labor rights
of South Korean employees at U.S. military bases are also expected
to be revised during the forthcoming talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0533 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Concerned Over Direction of Pakistan Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- India expressed concern
Friday over the direction in which the situation in Pakistan was
moving and virtually ruled out immediate resumption of the stalled
bilateral dialogue with Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is effectively under martial law following a military
coup," said a spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry. "We have
concerns about the direction in which the situation is moving."
</P>
<P>
"We continue to monitor and keep a close watch on these
developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the prospects of resumption of the stalled talks with
Pakistan, the spokesman said, "until the internal situation in
Pakistan becomes clear, it is difficult to say whether bilateral
talks could begin immediately."
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Friday that New Delhi's
concerns are in the context of the proclamation issued by
Pakistani Army Chief Pervez Musharraf enforcing a state of
emergency, keeping the Constitution in abeyance and declaring
himself the chief executive of the country.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after taking over as Indian prime minister on
Wednesday, Atal Bihari Vajpayee expressed grave concern over
developments in Islamabad, saying that vigilance on the
international border with Pakistan had been intensified but the
"situation is normal".
</P>
<P>
Asserting that it was for Islamabad to create the right climate
for resumption of stalled dialogue between the two neighbors, he
said that India's policy towards Islamabad was "consistent and
principled".
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said that his country remained committed to developing
friendly relations and cooperative ties with Pakistan based on
mutual trust and confidence for which the government of Pakistan
needs to create the right environment.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kashmir said that Indian security forces guarding
the northern borders with Pakistan were on full alert and any
attempt aimed at India "on the borders or inside" would receive a
befitting reply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
