<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA, Israel to Talk on Freeing More Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official said
on Friday that the Palestinian and Israeli sides would embark on
negotiations next week for the release of a third batch of
Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Prisoners Affairs Hisham Asaid the two sides will discu
ss the criteria for, and the
number of, those to be set free in the third group during
neasting, as stipulated
in the Sharm el-Sheikh memorandum the two sides signed in September.
</P>
<P>
Israel released 151 so-called Palestinian security prisoners
Friday morning as part of the implementation of this memorandum.
Eighty-three of the released were handed over to the Palestinian
side in Gaza, and the rest in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The release of the second batch of Palestinians had been
delayed for a week because of a dispute between the two sides over
precisely who should be freed.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side had insisted that the rules fixed in their
memorandum be followed, demanding the release of those serving
long, even life, sentences for actions against Israel before the
signing of the Oslo accords and detained before the Palestinian
self-rule came into force.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side, on the other hand, had insisted that 47
prisoners be replaced by others serving shorter sentences.
</P>
<P>
At long last, the two sides reached a compromise whereby the
Palestinian side agreed on the release of nine youngsters
sentences to two to three years, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
So far, Israel has released 350 Palestinian prisoners in two
batches since the signing of Sharm el-Sheikh memorandum which
brought the Mideast peace process back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
