<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Workers to Receive Pay Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Minimum wage earners in the
Philippine capital of Manila will receive a daily pay hike of
25.50 pesos (0.64 U.S. dollars) effective from December 29, the
Regional Tripartite Wage and Productivity Board announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, minimum wage earners in the Cagayan Valley region were
granted a pay hike of 10 to 12 pesos (0.25 to 0.3 U.S. dollars) by
the regional wage board, while those in Southern Mindanao were
given a minimum wage increase of 13 to 13.50 pesos (0.33 to 0.34
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma urged other regional wage
boards in the country to come up with new wage orders for minimum
wage adjustments as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said petitions
for wage adjustments should consider various factors, such as the
welfare of both the labor and management, the consumers and the
effect on the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Estrada reiterated that wage board decisions should ensure that
workers keep their jobs and business remains operational.
</P>
<P>
The president said drastic pay increases would most likely hurt
small and medium enterprises which comprise the majority of
private business in various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the economy's attractiveness to foreign investors
may also be diminished if very high wage increases are implemented
since overseas businessmen would opt to bring their investments in
countries where pay scales are lower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
