<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Declining in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 15 (Xinhua ) -- The poverty alleviation programs
undertaken by the Bangladeshi government have achieved remarkable
success with a gradual decline in the percentage of the poor in
the country since 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to "Three Years of Progress," a document on the
achievements of the current government led by Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina till June this year, poverty alleviation has been
given top priority since the ruling Awami League (the People's
League) came to power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The document released by the official Bangladesh News Agency
here Friday, citing surveys conducted by Bangladesh Bureau of
Statistics (BBS), said that about half of the population of 120
million were still in poverty in Bangladesh but there was marked
improvement that the percentage of poor people has been declining
with the implementation of scores of development programs
throughout the country since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The BBS recent surveys showed that the percentage of the poor
in rural areas declined from 47.9 percent in April 1996 to 47.6
percent in April 1998 and in urban areas from 44.4 percent to 44.3
percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
It was observed in the document that the Annual Development
Program with an allocation of around 70 billion taka (1.4 billion
U.S. dollars) for agriculture, rural development, water resources
development, primary education, health and family welfare, rural
electrification and local government, among other sectors, had
made direct and indirect contribution to poverty alleviation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The poverty alleviation programs were prioritized through
providing credit and training to unemployed youths and women for
self-employment under the purview of the 5th five-year plan to be
completed in the year 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
