<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Software Magnate Charged with Insider Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian software magnate
Michael Cowpland is being charged with insider trading and
prohibited from trading for at least 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The country's top securities regulator, the Ontario Securities
Commission (OSC), filed quasi-criminal charges against the
flamboyant entrepreneur in the Ontario Court of Justice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The OSC alleges that Cowpland, 56, sold shares of Corel for 20.
4 million Canadian dollars (about 13.8 million U.S. dollars) in
August 1997, after learning that Ottawa-based Corel Corp. would
fall far short of the third-quarter sales target of 94 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The OSC charged the Corel president with acting on insider
information through his personal company M.C.J.C. Holdings Inc.,
without disclosing to the public the anticipated sales shortfall.
</P>
<P>
The charges can result in a jail term of up to two years, plus
a maximum fine of 1 million Canadian dollars (about 675,400 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The OSC also slapped a 15-day ban on Cowpland and his personal
M.C.J.C. Holding Inc. from trading in Corel stock.
</P>
<P>
Corel has said that Cowpland and the company "continue to deny
all insider trading allegations."
</P>
<P>
According to the OSC sources, a court date has been set for
November 22, but the case will probably not get to trial until
late spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
