<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Keep Rights in Merging Aerospace and Defense Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- France will retain its rights in
the aerospace and defense group which is soon to be merged with
Germany, Agence France-Press said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Such rights include production control of ballistic missiles
that will be used in the French nuclear deterrence force, Agence
France-Presse quoted a source in the defense ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
France will sign a "convention" with the future European
Aeronautic, Defense and Space Co. (EADS), which will result from a
merger between Aerospatiale-Matra of France and DASA of Germany.
It will become the world's second largest missile maker after U.S.
Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
It said the convention will be drawn according to French laws
and will give France the right to protect its defense interests,
notably those concerned with ballistic missiles for its nuclear
deterrence force.
</P>
<P>
It said the French government will also maintain its "golden
share" or veto rights within the EADS, including the right to
block management decisions on mergers, acquisitions and takeovers,
and to decide upon the conception and integration of ballistic
missiles in the group.
</P>
<P>
The government will retain 47.7 percent of the shares of
Aerospatiale-Matra and will reduce to 15 percent its shares in
EADS when it is set up in the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The French Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot said
Friday that the government shares in EADS will never disappear.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a conflict (with Germany), the French side will
have the right to buy back," said Gayssot in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Daimler Chrysler, a German private group which owns DASA, has
urged France to privatize completely the Aerospatiale-Matra and
withdraw government interference from the group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0556 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgian Gunmen Release Kidnapped U.N. Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Georgian gunmen who
abducted six U.N. military observers and an interpreter on
Wednesday have released all their captives, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported Friday, quoting law enforcement sources from the
former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers released two U.N. observers and their
interpreter Friday. Four other hostages were freed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear if a ransom was paid. The gunmen had
reportedly demanded 200,000 U.S. dollars and later raised the
figure to 300,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. workers were abducted in the Kodori Valley, a remote
mountainous area situated in the breakaway region of Abkhazia but
controlled by Georgian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Tass said the gunmen have already left the Kodor Valley. A
helicopter is scheduled to transport them to Kutaisi, Georgia,
from where they will go to Sukhumi, the capital city of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The hostage release came after intensive negotiations between
the terrorists and high-ranking Georgian officials, including
Defense Minister David Tevzadze and President Eduard Shevardnadze'
s representative in the Kodor Valley, Iveri Chelidze, Tass said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
