<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Urges Taiwanese to Release Inland Chinese Fishermen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) today called for the release of
the 40 inland Chinese fishermen being willfully detained by Taiwan
army and police.
</P>
<P>
According to ARATS officials, about 200 fishermen from Zhejiang
and Fujian provinces have been detained by Taiwan army and police
in the first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Forty fishermen and 12 fishing boats remain in custody of
Taiwanese police.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS officials said that the Taiwan police should stop
detaining inland Chinese fishermen for no reason, and cease
inhumane behaviors such as assaulting and humiliating the
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
"The detained fishermen and their boats should be released as
soon as possible," the officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with Fujian Province, on August 31, the
Minshi--6111 fishing boat, while operating in the Taiwan Straits,
was stopped by a Taipei Police cruise vessel on the allegation of
carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
The boat owner, Cai Liangman, was beaten for being slow to open
a cabinet on the ship. Police aimed their guns at the crew members
and forced them to kneel.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS officials said that the wrongdoings by the Taiwanese
army and police have been detrimental to the life, livelihood and
property of the inland Chinese fishermen, and caused relevant
departments on the mainland greatly concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0558 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Embrace Challenges With Greater Enthusiasm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China, as the largest
developing nation in the world, is seizing the opportunities and
embracing the challenges with a more open mentality and greater
enthusiasm, a senior trade official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yu Xiaosong, chairman of China Council for the Promotion of
International trade (CCPIT), made the remarks at the Third Annual
Business Week CEO Forum, which was held at the Grand Hyatt Hotel
from October 13 to 15.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, China's economic growth achieved an
average rate of 7.7 percent, 2.5 times that of the world's average
level in the same period, laying a solid foundation for the
sustained development of the country in the next century, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
However, the changes of international economic environment and
the problems that have cropped up in the reform process are
undoubtedly challenges for China, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the new century, Yu said the Chinese government and business
community will, from a new perspective, make a choice on the
orientation of the country's development that is suitable to its
realities.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that globalization has shown a growing momentum in
recent years. The high-level decision-making bodies in China have
realized the necessity to accelerate the technological revamping
and industrial upgrading of state-owned enterprise in order to
adapt to the great trend of structural readjustment of global
industries and changes of demand on domestic and foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the sustained, rapid and healthy development
of China's economy has provided a large market for investors from
all around the world.
</P>
<P>
With continued reform and development of state-owned
enterprises, Yu said foreign investors are offered favorable
opportunities whether in terms of technology, capital or
structural readjustment.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, the Chinese government will adopt preferential
policies to encourage foreign investors to invest in the middle
and western part of the country," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"China will also adopt more open and liberal policies for
foreign investment in order to participate in the international
division of labor on a larger scale," Yu added.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has enlarged the areas of foreign
investment in the sectors of commercial circulation, foreign trade,
finance, insurance and tourism, and considerations are being made
to open accounting and legal services to foreign investment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue whether China can enter the WTO or not is a matter
of grave concern for both China and the rest of the world," Yu
said. "We have not changed our attitude and we still take an
active position."
</P>
<P>
In the new century, the CCPIT will make greater contributions
to the promotion of Sino-foreign economic and trade cooperation as
well as China's integration with the rest of the world, he
concluded.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 international business and political leaders,
including Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, and former U.S. president George Bush,
attended the forum with the theme of "Managing the speed of Change:
Meeting the Needs of Tomorrow". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
