<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0562 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number of Visitors to HK Electronics Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of visitors to the
19th Hong Kong Electronics Fair held between October 12 and 15
increased around 20 percent over that to the last event in 1998,
to nearly 40,000, according to the fair's independent auditor.
</P>
<P>
Half of the buyers were from overseas, which was around 24
percent more than in 1998. The largest number of visitors came
from Asia (up 23.28 percent), followed by Europe (up 20.16 percent)
and North America (up 24.22 percent).
</P>
<P>
The record participation of visitors indicates that there is an
increase in the demand for Hong Kong and Asian electronics
products, boosted in part by the recent revival in consumer
sentiment and an upturn in electronics production in the region,
said Allan Wong, chairman of Electronics/Electrical Appliances
Advisory Committee of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council,
organizer of the fair.
</P>
<P>
"If we look at the electronics industry with the Hong Kong
Electronics Fair as a lens, the view is definitely optimistic. It
is evident that both production and markets of the industry have
started ticking again," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
His views were shared by local and overseas exhibitors and
buyers.
</P>
<P>
Total exports of Hong Kong's electronics products from January
to August remained stable. Exports to Asian countries recorded the
highest growth rate. Total exports to South Korea, China's
mainland and Singapore increased by 59 percent, 9 percent and 4
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 20th Hong Kong Electronics Fair will be held from October
11 to 14, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
