<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 150 Die as Fighting Rages in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The heavy fighting at land and
at sea between government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels has left
more than 150 dead in Sri Lanka's north and east, officials here
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said in a statement that government troops
had recovered 55 bodies of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE), but the rebels' casualties could be well over one hundred
in an abortive attack on troops near Ampakamam in the northern
Wanni region late on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said air force jets and helicopters attacked retreating
rebels, and troops were in the process of pursuit and
consolidation following the fighting about 260 kilometers
northeast of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The statement said 19 soldiers were killed and 57 wounded in
the clash, the fiercest in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
A large number of rebels were also believed to have been
wounded in the fighting, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In a separate clash on Thursday night, Sri Lankan naval
gunboats attacked a flotilla of Tamil rebels' boats off Kokkilai
in the northeastern Mullaitivu district, about 270 kilometers
northeast of the capital, navy officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said some 30 guerrillas were killed when three boats were
caught fire and sunk and another boat was badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
Four sailors were wounded and four naval gunboats were slightly
damaged, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting for a separate homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991015.0568 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leprosy Eliminated in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China has brought down the
proportion of lepers in the Tibetan Autonomous Region to 0.002
percent to date, well below the 0.01 percent level set as the
elimination point by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The number of lepers in Tibet stands at 61 at present, after a
total of 3,259 lepers were cured in the past three decades,
Thubden, director of the regional health bureau, said in an
interview with Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging result has been achieved thanks to "strenuous
efforts made by the central and regional governments," Thubden
said, noting that the proportion of lepers was as high as 0.06
percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy used to be one of the major diseases in Tibet, with
cases of the disease known as far back as 1,400 years ago. Under
the serf system in old Tibet, serfs had no access to medical
treatment and once they contracted leprosy, they were ousted from
their villages or even buried alive immediately.
</P>
<P>
Thubden said that since 1965 when the Tibetan Autonomous Region
was set up, the central and local governments have launched a
massive campaign to prevent the spread of leprosy and provide
proper medical treatment to lepers.
</P>
<P>
Some 15 hospitals specialized in treating leprosy have been
established in Tibet and modern treatment methods recommended by
the WHO have been adopted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of lepers began to fall in the 1970s. "
Now the Tibetan people are glad that they do not have to be afraid
of the disease any more," Thubden said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
