<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKTA Opens Office in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA) opened an office today in Shanghai, the nation'
s largest trade and financial center.
</P>
<P>
This is the second office that HKTA has opened in China's
inland; the first is in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with HKTA, the number of tourists from the
Chinese provinces to Hong Kong has been increasing over the past
few years. Total arrivals reached 2.6 million in 1998, up 13
percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tourists from Shanghai, and Jiangsu and Zhejiang
provinces accounted for 15 percent of the total, only next to the
figure of Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, about 6.8 million
visitors arrived in Hong Kong, with inland tourist making up a
third of the total arrivals.
</P>
<P>
HKTA officials expressed their intentions to further expand
business in China's inland, and promote tourist routes to the
scenic landscapes of the Pearl River Delta, and Beijing, Xi'an and
Guilin cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
